1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6
8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Ne5 10. Kb1 {In the theoretical part we analyse 10 Ne5,
but this was played before that move rose to prominence.} c6 11. Be2 Ng4 12.
Bd3 {Now we see Anand's idea - he wants to keep the light-squared bishop for
the attack.} (12. Bd4 $5 {was another, more complicated way, to achieve the
same exchange of a dark-squared bishop for a knight.} c5 13. h3 cxd4 14. hxg4
dxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxg4 16. Qb4 $14 {looks better for White, though in an open
position like this organising an attack is not really feasible.}) 12... d5 $6 {
This doesn't look too much in line with Black's last move. As the continuation
of the game shows perhaps this was based on missing White's 15th move.} ({
It was more natural to take the bishop} 12... Nxe3 13. Qxe3 Re8 14. Rhe1 Be6
15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Qf4 d5 17. h4 Bc5 {and Black managed to avoid the attack
because after} 18. h5 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Qb8 $1 20. Qf3 Qf8 21. a3 Re8 {he managed
to exchange pretty much everything. 1/2-1/2 (26) Juárez de Vena,A (2146)
-Arambulo Urdaneta,H ICCF 2016}) 13. Bf4 $1 {Now the knight on g4 has only
wasted time.} Bd6 14. h3 $1 Bxf4 15. Bxh7+ $1 {Maybe Kasimdzhanov missed this
move, without which Black would have been fine?} Kh8 (15... Kxh7 16. hxg4+ Bh6
17. g5 {wins a piece.}) 16. Qxf4 Nxf2 17. Ng5 {White's attack is overwhelming.
Quite an instructive example how quickly White's attack can become decisive in
these structures.} f6 18. Nf7+ $1 Rxf7 19. Bg6 Nxd1 (19... f5 20. Qxf2 {
and the attack continues with equal material.}) 20. Qh4+ Kg8 21. Re1 $1 {
Cutting off the king's escape via the e-file.} Nxc3+ 22. bxc3 Be6 23. Rxe6 Qb6+
24. Kc1 1-0

