1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O
8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Re8 10. h4 (10. Bd3 {is what we analyse in the theoretical
part.}) 10... c6 11. h5 (11. Bd3 {would still transpose, but it is possible to
treat this opening position in many ways.}) 11... h6 {Black normally wants to
avoid White pushing h6, and the hook on h6 can be defended by ...Bf8.} 12. Kb1
Nf6 13. Bd3 Bf8 14. Rdg1 {White's play is very straight-forward - he finished
development and now wants to push g4-g5.} Ng4 {Mechanically preventing the
push.} (14... d5 15. g4 $1 Nxg4 16. Bxh6 $1 {shows one of White's ideas. Now
play gets murky} (16. Bf4 {/\Rh4 is another way to play.}) 16... gxh6 17. Nh2
f5 18. f3 Qg5 $1 {Black must play very precisely to avoid opening the files
against his king.} 19. Qd1 Bc5 20. Rg2 Bd6 $1 (20... Nf2 21. Rxg5+ hxg5 22. Qg1
Nxh1 23. Qxg5+ Kf7 24. Qg6+ Ke7 25. h6 $16 {looks very promising for White.})
21. fxg4 Bxh2 22. Rgxh2 fxg4 (22... f4 {keeps the g-file closed and is also
rather unclear.}) 23. Rg1 g3 24. Rhg2 Re3 {looks very edgy for Black, but he
somehow holds}) 15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Nh2 {Removing the mechanical obstacle in the
way of the g-pawn.} Nxh2 {Gelfand goes for simplifications, but these don't
help Black in these lines as White's kingside initiative continues even with
few pieces left on the board.} (16... Ne5 17. g4 Nxd3 18. cxd3 {/\g5 looks
menacing enough, though the engine is confident Black is fine here after} Qe7
19. Be3 $5 (19. g5 $140 hxg5 20. Bxg5 Qe2 $1) 19... f6 20. Nf1 {in a rather
typical way White continues with his active play on the kingside while Black
is without much active counterplay. This scenario is typical of this line.})
17. Rxh2 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Qxf5 19. g4 Qe4 20. g5 hxg5 21. Bxg5 {Black exchanged
almost all light pieces, but White's attack didn't become less strong because
of that.} Qe2 $6 {Attempting to avoid the attack Gelfand sacrifices material
and transposes to an endgame.} (21... Re6 {is the engine's preference} 22. Rh4
Qf5 23. Rf4 Qh7 24. Qd1 Rae8 25. Rb4 $1 b5 26. Be3 {is still unpleasant for
Black, but at least he's not down material. The rook from b4 will now return
to the kingside.}) 22. Qxe2 Rxe2 23. Be3 {Black loses the exchange now and
should be technically lost.} Rxe3 24. fxe3 Re8 25. Rh3 $18 {The rest of the
game is not of theoretical interest, so I will only note the critical moments.}
Re6 26. c4 Be7 27. Rf3 Re5 28. Rgf1 Rxh5 29. Rxf7 Re5 30. R7f3 Bf6 31. c3 Re4
32. Rxf6 $5 {Possibly not the best, but an interesting practical decision. The
rook endgame is still tricky for Black.} (32. Rd1 Re6 (32... Be5 33. c5 $1) 33.
Kc2 Kf7 34. Kd3 {was a more "normal" way to continue.}) 32... gxf6 33. Rxf6
Rxe3 34. Rxd6 Kf7 35. Kc2 $2 (35. Rd8 $1 {is better, according to the engine,
the point being that after} b6 36. c5 $1 bxc5 37. Rc8 {White managed to
exchange his doubled c-pawn for Black's c-or a-pawn (in view or Rc7xa7).})
35... Re2+ 36. Kb3 Ke7 37. Rd4 {Black's problem is that his king is cut off,
but he should be able to draw.} c5 38. Rd3 b6 39. Ka3 Rc2 $6 (39... Re4 $1 {
attacks the c4-pawn and prevents b4.} 40. b3 Rg4 41. Ka4 a6 {and without
b4-ideas White cannot do much.}) 40. Rd5 a5 (40... a6 41. Rd3 {/\b4}) 41. Rd3
Rh2 42. b3 Rc2 (42... Rh4 43. Rd2 {/\Ka4-b5.}) 43. Ka4 {The last attempt.}
Rxa2+ 44. Kb5 Rb2 45. Kxb6 a4 46. Kxc5 Rxb3 47. Kc6 a3 48. c5 Ke8 49. Rh3 a2 $4
(49... Ke7 $8 {should still draw.}) 50. Rh8+ Ke7 51. Ra8 {Now it's winning for
White.} Rb2 52. Kc7 Rc2 53. c6 Rb2 54. c4 Rc2 55. Ra6 Rb2 56. c5 Ke6 57. Ra5
Rc2 58. Kb7 Rb2+ 59. Kc8 Ke7 60. c7 Ke8 61. Rxa2 $1 Rxa2 62. Kb7 {The king
conveniently hides on c6, making perfect use of the doubled c-pawns formed as
early as move 6.} 1-0

[Event "chess.com Junior Speed"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
[Date "2019.07.28"]
[Round "3.18"]
[White "Firouzja, Alireza"]
[Black "Wei Yi"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C42"]
[WhiteElo "2682"]
[BlackElo "2736"]
[Annotator "GM Alex Colovic"]
[PlyCount "103"]
[EventDate "2019.05.16"]
[EventType "k.o. (blitz)"]
[EventRounds "4"]
[EventCountry "USA"]
[SourceTitle "The Week in Chess 1290"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]
[SourceDate "2019.07.29"]
[SourceVersion "2"]
[SourceVersionDate "2019.07.30"]
[SourceQuality "2"]

{The following games were played as part of the speed-chess online match-up on
28 July 2019. Even though they were blitz games and the quality cannot be
expected to be too high, these games featured two of the brightest young
talents in the world. Additionally, in speed chess the intuition and easiness
of play comes to the fore, thus giving us a better idea how it feels to play
these positions with both colours.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Qd2 Be6 9. a3 {A peculiar move-order,
but soon leading to what we analysed.} Qd7 10. O-O-O {Now we reach the
position from the famous Karjakin-Caruana game from the Berlin Candidates,
analysed in the theoretical section.} h6 {Wei Yi follows Caruana. The main
alternative is the move 10...a6.} 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O {In case if 10...
a6 this is the right way to play, but here the hook on h6 gives White
something to latch onto. I criticised this move in the analytical section, but
perhaps things are not that simple.} 13. c4 {This is a slower approach and it
allows Black to consolidate.} (13. Rg1 {is the move I recommended, withouth
going into more depth. White's play is simple: g4-g5.}) 13... Rae8 {Black's
plan is to play ...f5 followed by ...Bf6, thus concentrating all his forces on
the kingside.} 14. Qc3 (14. h4 f5 15. Be2 {/\Bh5 is what the engine suggests
and then after ...Bf7 to return to f3.}) 14... f5 15. Kb1 (15. Bxg7 $4 Bg5+) (
15. f4 $5 Bf6 16. c5 {is how the engine pushes forward and it does look
annoying for Black with the uncomfortable pressure on the d-file.}) 15... Bf6
16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Bd3 {All three games reached this position.} Qc6 (17... b6 {
was played in the third game and we can assume it should have been an
improvement. Black doesn't waste time on ...Qc6 and then recapturing ...Qc6xe8.
} 18. Rhe1 a5 19. Re2 (19. f3 Bf7 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Qd4 {looks around equal.})
(19. b3 {is the engine's suggestion, again with an equal position.}) 19... Bf7
20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. f3 Bg6 (21... Qe3 $1 {would have been more annoying for
White.}) 22. Qd2 Qe7 23. b3 Kf8 24. h4 Re6 25. Rh1 (25. g4 $5 fxg4 26. Bxg6
Rxg6 27. h5 Rg5 28. fxg4 {is again around equal, though White's king is safer
than Black's.}) 25... Qf6 26. h5 Bf7 27. Qf4 $2 (27. g4) 27... Re5 28. a4 Be6
$2 (28... Bxh5 $1 {wins a pawn in view of the back-rank problems White has.})
29. Rd1 Qg5 30. Qxg5 hxg5 31. Rh1 {with an equal endgame that eventually Black
won. 0-1 (50) Firouzja,A (2682)-Wei Yi (2736) chess.com INT 2019}) 18. f3 b6
19. Rhe1 a5 20. Re2 Bf7 21. Rxe8+ Qxe8 {We have the same structure with the
same material balance in all 3 games. The position is equal, though playing
White seems a tad easier.} 22. f4 (22. b3 Qe5 $2 {This attempt at immediate
simplification is a blunder:} 23. Qxe5 dxe5 24. Re1 {wins a pawn} e4 25. fxe4
fxe4 26. Rxe4 Rf2 27. Re7 c5 28. Rb7 Rxg2 (28... Kf8 29. Rxb6 Rxg2 30. h3 Rg3
31. Bf5 $18) 29. Rb8+ {1-0 (29) Firouzja,A (2682)-Wei Yi (2736) chess.com INT
2019}) 22... Qe7 (22... Qe3 $1) 23. g3 Kf8 24. b3 Bh5 25. Rf1 Bg4 {This game
is the most characteristic one, as in the maneuvering phase White manages to
outplay Black from an equal position.} 26. Qd4 Re6 27. Qd5 Re1+ $2 {Impatience.
} (27... Qf6 28. c5 $5 dxc5 29. Bc4 {poses some problems} Be2 (29... Re4 {
looks scary to allow the check from g8, but Black is OK} 30. Qg8+ Ke7 31. Qc8
Qd6) 30. Qxe6 Qxe6 31. Bxe6 Bxf1 32. Bxf5 $11) 28. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 29. Ka2 $16 {
The endgame is difficult for Black because of his more exposed king and weak
queenside pawns.} Qf2 30. b4 {This is also possible.} (30. Qc6 Qc5 31. Qd7 {
Black is paralysed to the defence of c7 and f7.} Bh3 32. a4 $1 {preventing ...
a4 ideas.} Bg4 33. Qe6 Bh3 34. Be2 $1 {/\Bh5} Bg4 35. Bxg4 fxg4 36. Qxg4 {
winning a pawn with what should be a winning endgame.}) 30... axb4 31. axb4
Qxh2 $2 {This leaves the queen offside. Even taking on g3 won't help Black
much because his kingside pawns are more difficult to set in motion than
White's on the queenside.} 32. Qa8+ (32. Qb7 $1 $18) 32... Ke7 33. Qc8 $6 (33.
c5 $1) 33... c5 $1 34. Qc7+ Ke6 35. Qxb6 Qf2 36. b5 Be2 37. Qc6 Bxd3 38. Qd5+
Kd7 39. Qxd3 g6 {This should be around equal, but still easier for White with
the protected passed pawn.} 40. Kb3 Qe1 41. c3 Qc1 42. Qc2 Qxc2+ $2 {Making
things more complicated for himself.} (42... Qf1 $11) 43. Kxc2 Kc7 $4 (43... g5
$8 44. g4 $1 fxg4 45. fxg5 g3 46. gxh6 g2 47. h7 g1=Q 48. h8=Q Qf2+ 49. Kb3 Qf1
{with a probably drawn queen endgame.}) 44. Kd3 $18 Kb6 45. Ke3 Kc7 46. Kf3 {
/\g4} g5 47. g4 $1 fxg4+ 48. Kxg4 gxf4 49. Kxf4 Kb6 50. Kf5 Kc7 51. Kg6 Kb6 52.
Kxh6 1-0

