1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d4 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8.
Bd3 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1 (10. Nh4 $1 {was recommended in the theoretical part.
}) 10... Nbd7 11. d5 $14 {This is White's main positional idea when Black
fianchettoes the bishop on b7 - the shuts the bishop and fixes the light
squares.} Re8 12. a4 Bf8 13. Rxe8 Qxe8 14. Bg5 Nxd5 $2 {Black wasn't very
comfortable, but this transformation is in White's favour.} (14... a6 {was
better. Being patient is the single most important characteristic the Black
player must have when playing these positions.} 15. Qd2 (15. Bc4 Ne4 $1) 15...
h6 16. Re1 Qc8 {/\Nd5 now as h7 isn't hanging} 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Bc4 g6 19. Nd4
Bg7 {with a passive but very solid position for Black.}) 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16.
Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 17. Qxd5 Ne5 18. Nd4 {It may not look like much for White, but
this deceptive - a better king, more active pieces (particularly the bishop)
and weak light squares on the queenside for Black make it very easy to play
for him. At first the engine evaluates this around zero, but then it slowly
changes its mind.} f6 19. Bf4 c6 20. Qe4+ Ng6 {Black was already faced with a
tough choice.} (20... Qg6 21. Qxg6+ (21. Qe2 {/\Ra3 is a pleasant middlegame.})
21... Kxg6 22. a5 b5 23. a6 $1 $14 {is a pleasant endgame for White.}) (20...
Kg8 21. Bxe5 $1 {><c6} d5 22. Qg4 fxe5 23. Nf5 $36) 21. Qf5 $1 Kg8 22. Bg3 {
/\Nc6.} Ne5 23. f4 Nf7 24. Re1 Qc8 25. Qg6 {White is practically winning - all
his pieces are attacking while Black's are disorganised.} Nh6 (25... Nh8 {
is the engine's suggestion, but this gives you an idea of the state Black's in.
}) 26. f5 c5 27. Ne6 Qe8 28. Nc7 (28. c4 {is the sadistic suggestion of the
engine.}) 28... Qxg6 29. fxg6 Rc8 30. Nd5 Nf5 31. Bf2 {Black's kingside is
completely paralysed.} Nd4 32. Bxd4 cxd4 33. b4 a5 34. Nxb6 Rxc2 35. Re8 Rc7
36. bxa5 d3 37. Kf2 Rc2+ 38. Kf3 1-0

