1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6
8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Ne5 10. Kb1 (10. Nxe5 {is analysed in the theoretical part.
}) 10... a6 11. Be2 Be6 12. Nd4 Nc4 $6 (12... Bd7 $142) 13. Qd3 {/\Ne6} Nxe3
14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Qxe3 e5 16. Bd3 $16 {We have a position with
opposite-coloured bishops where White is clearly better - his bishop is active
and can help with an attack on the kingside while Black's is limited by its
own pawns, which only make Black's light squares even weaker.} c6 17. h4 Rf6
18. g3 d5 $2 {Positionally correct, to put the pawns on light squares, but
this fails due to the opening of the position for which White is better
prepared.} (18... Qc7 {was better, though not fun to play. An illustrative
line is} 19. f4 exf4 20. Qe4 Rh6 21. Rde1 Bf6 22. Qxf4 Be5 23. Qg4 $16) 19.
Qxe5 Rxf2 20. Rhf1 {This is good enough.} (20. Rde1 $1 {/\Qh5 is winning
according to the engine.} Bf8 21. Qh5 g6 22. Qg4 {/\h5.}) 20... Rf6 21. Qh5 $1
g6 22. Qe2 {Now White can further weaken the position of Black's king by h5.}
Qd6 23. h5 Raf8 24. hxg6 hxg6 25. Rh1 {Black is losing, he cannot defend
long-term against the attack.} Kf7 26. c4 $1 {Opening a second front.} Ke8 27.
cxd5 c5 (27... cxd5 28. Rhe1) 28. g4 Kd8 29. g5 (29. Rhe1 $1) 29... Rf4 30. Rh6
Bxg5 31. Rxg6 Bf6 32. Rh6 $6 {Anand's play wasn't the most precise and he
gives Black chances to save himself.} (32. c3) 32... Qe5 (32... Re8 33. Qd2 c4
$1) 33. c3 Qxe2 34. Bxe2 Rf2 35. Bg4 {But even here Black has a lot to suffer..
.} b5 (35... Rg8 $142) 36. d6 (36. Rh7) 36... Rg8 37. Bh3 b4 $2 (37... Rg3 $142
38. Rh7 Bg7) 38. Rh7 $1 $18 bxc3 39. bxc3 Rg3 (39... Rh8 40. Rxh8+ Bxh8 41. Rg1
$1) 40. Re1 $2 (40. Rd7+ Ke8 41. Rc7 $1 {wins on the spot as the d-pawn
promotes.}) 40... Be5 $2 (40... Bg7 41. d7 Rf8 42. Re4 {should still win,
though it would take some time.}) 41. Rd7+ {Now it's over.} Kc8 42. Rf7+ Rxh3
43. Rxf2 Bxd6 44. Kc2 Kd7 45. Ree2 Kc6 46. Rf6 Kc7 47. Ree6 Rh2+ 48. Kd3 Rh3+
49. Kc4 Rh4+ 50. Kb3 c4+ 51. Ka4 Rh2 52. Rxd6 1-0

