1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O
8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O c5 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. Rhe1 (11. Bg5) 11... Be6 12. Bg5 h6 $4 {
The game loses its theoretical significance now, but it is because of this
game that we know that the move 12...h6 is losing. After the sacrifice we see
a typical attack from White in this line.} (12... d5 13. Qf4 Re8 14. Re5 $5 (
14. Bb5 Rf8 {1/2-1/2 (17) Karjakin,S (2748)-So,W (2763) Riga LAT 2019}) 14...
Qc7 15. Qh4 h6 16. Bxh6 Ne4 {was very complicated in ½-½ (100) Navara,D 
(2739)-Gelfand,B (2655) Prague CZE 2019}) 13. Bxh6 $1 $18 c4 (13... gxh6 14.
Qxh6 Re8 15. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 (15... Bf8 16. Rxe8 Qxe8 17. Qxf6 $18) 16. Ng5 {
is a nice mating sequence.}) 14. Bxg7 $1 cxd3 (14... Kxg7 15. Qg5+ Kh8 16. Qh6+
Kg8 17. Ng5 {mates for White.}) 15. Qg5 Ne4 (15... Nh7 16. Qg3 Bg5+ 17. Nxg5
Qxg5+ 18. Qxg5 Nxg5 19. Bxf8 dxc2 20. Rxd6 Kxf8 21. h4 $18 {transposes to the
game.}) 16. Qh6 Bg5+ 17. Nxg5 Qxg5+ 18. Qxg5 Nxg5 19. Bxf8 dxc2 20. Rxd6 Kxf8
21. h4 $18 {Is a winning endgame for White as the pawns are rolling and he
will have a rook and three pawns for the two light pieces. Karjakin won
without too many issues.} Nh7 22. Kxc2 Nf6 23. f3 Ke7 24. Rd4 Rh8 25. c4 Nd7
26. b3 a6 27. Kc3 Nb8 28. g3 Nc6 29. Rd2 Kf6 30. Rh2 b5 31. cxb5 axb5 32. Rd2
Rh5 33. Re3 Ne7 34. Re4 Rf5 35. Rd3 Rc5+ 36. Kd2 Nf5 37. Rg4 Rc8 38. Rc3 Ra8
39. Rc2 Ne7 40. Rf4+ Kg7 41. Ke1 Nd5 42. Rd4 Kf6 43. Kf2 Ke5 44. Re4+ Kd6 45.
h5 Ke7 46. g4 Kd6 47. Rd2 f5 48. gxf5 Bxf5 49. h6 Rh8 50. Red4 Be6 51. Rh4 Ke7
52. Rh5 Nf6 53. Rxb5 Rxh6 54. a4 Rh1 55. a5 Nd7 56. b4 Bc4 57. Rg5 Ke6 58. Rd4
Rc1 59. a6 Rc2+ 60. Kg3 Bf1 61. a7 Nb6 62. Rd1 1-0

