1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6
8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 10. Kb1 {This is another popular move in the tabiya.
White makes a useful move and doesn't determine what he's going to do next.}
Bf6 {The main move for Black.} (10... a6) (10... h6) 11. Bg5 $5 {But this is
rather rare.} (11. h4 {is by far the most common move here, for example} O-O-O
12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Be5 $1 {Black manages to avoid the weakning of his
structure with this move.} 14. Be2 Qa4 15. b3 Qa5 {1/2-1/2 (40) Vachier
Lagrave,M (2779)-Caruana,F (2822) Saint Louis USA 2018}) 11... Qe7 (11... Bxg5
12. Nxg5 O-O-O 13. Nxe6 $14 {is a slightly better position for White whichever
Black recaptures on e6.}) 12. Bb5 {White's play in this line is interesting -
he plays for a microscopic advantage based on his better structure. This is
very safe, but also very difficult to convert into something more tangible.} a6
{Forcing White's hand. Otherwise he may change his mind, for example} (12...
O-O 13. h4 $1) 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qf4 (14. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 15. Nd4 {is the
engine's suggestion after which it continues with} Kd7 $5 (15... Bd5 16. c4
Bxc4 17. Nxc6 O-O 18. Rhe1 $14 {White has a stable advantage here due to the
better structure.}) 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 (16... fxe6 17. Rhe1 $14) 17. Rhe1 Qf5 18.
Qd4 $14 {White is better, as he can play for a long time against Black's
"centralised" king.}) 14... Bxg5 15. Nxg5 O-O 16. Rde1 Qd7 17. f3 $6 (17. Nxe6
fxe6 18. Qd2 $14 {is what we get in the game later on.}) 17... h6 $2 {Black
insists on the exchange, but the ensuing positions are tough for him.} (17...
Bf5 18. g4 {was what probably Giri was afraid of, but he has} f6 $1 19. Ne4 Bg6
20. h4 $6 f5 $1) 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qg4 $14 {White has a stable advantage here
due to his better structure, which in this case means play against Black's
pawn mass in the centre and also the isolated pawn on a6.} Rf5 20. Re2 e5 21.
Rd1 Qf7 22. Qb4 (22. Qe4 d5 (22... Qd7 23. c4 {/\c5}) 23. Qb4 Qd7 24. c4 $16 {
continues the attack against Black's centre.}) 22... Qd7 23. Qa4 Kh8 24. c4 {
/\c5.} Qe8 25. Rd3 (25. c5 $1 {was still possible.} d5 26. Rde1 a5 27. Qd4 $1
$16 Qg6 28. Qd3 Rg5 29. Qxg6 Rxg6 30. g3 Rf8 31. Rxe5 Rxf3 32. a3 {and the
rook endgame is probably lost for Black due to the too many pawn weaknesses.})
25... Rf4 26. Qa5 Qe7 27. c5 $1 {A typical move in these structures,
effectively breaking down Black's central mass.} Rf6 (27... d5 28. Rde3 Rf5 29.
g4 {wins the e5-pawn.}) 28. Qc3 Qe8 29. b3 Rb8 30. a4 $18 {Black is helpless
so White can take time to improve his position.} Ra8 31. Re4 Qc8 32. Qd2 Qf8
33. Qa5 Qe7 34. Rde3 Qd7 35. Re1 Rf5 36. Qc3 Rd8 37. g3 {Topalov decides to
push f4.} (37. Qd3 Qc8 38. cxd6 cxd6 39. Rb4 {/\Rb6 is a way suggested by the
engine.}) 37... Rf7 38. cxd6 cxd6 39. f4 exf4 40. gxf4 {/\Re6.} c5 (40... d5
41. Re6 d4 42. Qxc6) 41. Re6 Rxf4 (41... Kg8 42. f5 {/\f6} Rxf5 $140 43. Re7)
42. Rxh6+ Kg8 43. Qd2 Rf7 44. Rg1 {Eventually the game is decided by a direct
attack on the king.} c4 45. Qg5 Rdf8 46. Qh5 Rf1+ 47. Kb2 1-0

