{[%evp 0,39,25,22,22,17,22,25,47,47,44,28,59,52,55,31,43,44,35,52,44,46,68,33,
47,12,10,9,5,15,15,15,37,36,56,57,51,58,55,56,70,59]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3.
Nxe5 d6 (3... Nxe4 $6 {This looks amateurish and indeed it leads to a better
endgame for White after} 4. Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3 $1
{The simplest.} (8. Bb5 {is an alternative, but after} Bd7 9. Nc3 O-O-O {
Black is getting his wish to muddy the waters.}) 8... Qxe5 (8... Nxe5 $2 {
loses the pawn on c7 after} 9. Bf4 Ng6 (9... f6 $2 10. Nd5 $18 {is even worse})
10. Qxe7+ Bxe7 11. Bxc7) 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Bf4 Bd6 11. Bg3 O-O (11... f6 12.
O-O-O {/\Nb5 is the key idea for White in this line - to take the bishop on d6
and obtain a better structure and the bishop pair.}) 12. O-O-O Bf5 $4 {a
surprising blunder by such a strong player like Sengupta.} (12... Be6 13. Nb5
Rfd8 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. Be2 {is what White is trying to achieve in this line.})
13. Rd5 $1 {White wins material now.} Be6 14. Bxe5 Bxd5 15. Bxd6 Bxg2 16. Bxg2
cxd6 17. Bxb7 Rae8 18. Bc6 $18 {1-0 (30) Vocaturo,D (2612)-Sengupta,D (2559)
Porticcio FRA 2019}) 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 ({For illustrative purposes, here's a
famous game with the same plan of ...Nf6 for Black.} 5. d4 Be7 6. Bd3 Nf6 7. h3
$1 {Preventing ...Bg4.} O-O 8. O-O c6 (8... c5) (8... Re8) 9. Re1 Nbd7 10. Bf4
Re8 11. c4 {This is not possible in the line with 5 Nc3, hence the logic
behind Black's 5...Nf6.} Nf8 12. Nc3 {White is better here, but Black is very
solid, which is what he was trying to achieve anyway. It is curious to note
that Petrosian outplayed Fischer from this position! I give the rest of the
game with short comments.} a6 13. Qb3 Ne6 14. Bh2 Bf8 15. Re2 (15. a4 $1 a5 16.
Re2) 15... b5 $1 $132 16. Qc2 Bb7 17. Rae1 g6 18. b4 $2 bxc4 $6 (18... a5 $1)
19. Bxc4 Nc7 (19... d5 $1) 20. Bb3 $6 (20. Rxe8 $1 Ncxe8 21. Qb3 d5 22. Bf1 Nd6
23. Na4 $14) 20... Rxe2 21. Rxe2 Ncd5 22. a3 $6 (22. Nxd5 cxd5 23. Qc1 Rc8 24.
Rc2) 22... a5 $1 $36 23. Nxd5 cxd5 24. b5 a4 $1 25. Ba2 Qb6 26. Qb1 Ra5 $6 (
26... Ne4 $1) 27. Rb2 $11 Ne4 28. Bf4 Nc3 29. Qc2 Rxb5 30. Rxb5 Nxb5 31. Qxa4
Qa6 32. Qxa6 Bxa6 33. Be3 Nxa3 34. Bxd5 Bc4 35. Bc6 Nc2 36. Bd2 Be2 37. Be4
Bxf3 38. Bxc2 {½-½ (38) Fischer,R-Petrosian,T, Buenos Aires Candidates m/5
1971}) 5... Nf6 {The main move 5...Nc3 is considered in the next two chapters.
This move is not very popular but it certainly has some logic. The idea is to
obtain a solid position, perhaps something a-la the fifth match game
Fischer-Petrosian above, but in a better version for Black as White cannot
follow Fischer's plan with c2-c4.} 6. d4 Be7 7. Bd3 {White can start with 7 h3,
but since 7...Bg4 isn't very good it is practically better to start with the
bishop move, tempting Black to go ...Bg4.} O-O (7... Bg4 $6 {"taking
advantage" of the omission of h3, but here White has} 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 $1 Bg6 {
Black will manage to exchange the light-squared bishops, but he has allowed
White to expand on the kingside and also obtain a development advantage.} 10.
Be3 c6 (10... d5 $6 11. Ne5 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 c6 13. O-O-O $16 {the symmetrical
position brings no safety for Black here.}) (10... Nc6 $6 11. g5 Nd7 12. h4 $16
) 11. g5 $1 ({Even wasting a tempo with} 11. Qe2 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 {was good for
White, only emphasising the strength of White's position.} Na6 {1-0 (61)
Rublevsky,S (2676)-Adams,M (2729) Moscow 2007} 13. a3 $1 Nc7 14. O-O-O Qd7 (
14... O-O 15. g5 Nfd5 (15... Nh5 16. d5 c5 17. Ne4 $16) 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. h4
$16 {Black is without counterplay as White advances on the kingside.}) 15. g5
Nfd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bd2 O-O-O 18. c4 Nc7 19. d5 {White is better here,
though Black can perhaps hope to save a draw in the endgame after} cxd5 20.
cxd5 Qb5 21. Be3 Qxd3 22. Rxd3 Kb8 23. h4 f6 $14) 11... Nfd7 (11... Nd5 12.
Nxd5 cxd5 13. h4 $16 {White is much better here as the straightening-up of the
structure after} Be4 {leads to problems for Black after} 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2
d5 16. f3 exf3 17. Qxf3 Nc6 18. O-O-O {as his main problem is the lack of safe
haven for the king.}) 12. h4 Bh5 13. Ne4 (13. d5 $16 {is the engine's
suggestion}) 13... Na6 14. c3 Nc7 15. Ng3 Bg4 16. Bf5 {with an advantage for
White, though Karpov managed to draw in: 1/2-1/2 (56) Muzychuk,M (2491)-Karpov,
A (2619) Cap d'Agde 2013}) 8. h3 Nc6 {The idea of this move is to play ...Nb4
and when the bishop moves follow up with ...Bf5, hitting c2. Apart from this
one Black has several other plans at his disposal.} (8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nh4
$1 {Immediately taking advantage of the bishop leaving the h3-c8 diagonal. The
most common move has been 10 Re1, but this is stronger. Now Black needs to
decide whether to allow Nf5 or not.} Re8 (10... g6 11. Bh6 $1 ({Wei Yi played} 
11. f4 {immediately, but attacking the rook first is stronger: 1-0 (25) Wei Yi
(2734)-Fang,Y (2499) Tianjin CHN 2018} c5 $5 12. f5 cxd4 13. Ne2 {is still
promising for White.}) 11... Re8 12. f4 Bf8 (12... c5 $2 {now doesn't work} 13.
f5 cxd4 14. fxg6 hxg6 15. Bxg6 $1 {is crushing} fxg6 $140 16. Qd3 $1) 13. Bxf8
Rxf8 14. f5 g5 15. Nf3 h6 16. Qd2 {/\h4->}) 11. Nf5 Bf8 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 g6
14. Ne3 Bg7 15. a4 $5 {a typical AlphaZero idea, suggested by Lc0! 15 Bc4, 15
Ne2, 15 Qd2 and 15 Re1 are valid alternatives.} a6 16. Bc4 Nc6 (16... Nbd7 $6
17. Qd3 Nf8 18. Rae1 {gives White strong initiative as Black is very passive.})
17. Bxf6 Bxf6 (17... Qxf6 18. Ncd5 Qd8 19. c3 Ne7 20. Qb3 {with very annoying
initiative for White.}) 18. Bd5 Rb8 19. Qg4 Kf8 20. Rfd1 {A strange move at
first sight, the rationale lies in the following line as after move 27 the
pawn on a4 is hanging.} (20. Rad1 {is possible, and if we follow the same line
then after} Bg7 21. Qf3 Qd7 22. Ne2 Kg8 23. Nf4 Ba8 24. c3 Ne7 {the pawn on a4
hangs, but White is still better after} 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 26. Ra1) 20... Bg7 21.
Qf3 Qd7 22. Ne2 Nd8 {this initiates curious complications} (22... Kg8 23. Nf4
Ba8 24. c3 Ne7 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 26. a5 b5 27. Nfd5 Nxd5 28. Nxd5 $16 {with a very
pleasant position for White, who has ideas like Nb4, tying Black down to the
defence of the a6-pawn.}) 23. Nf4 Kg8 24. Nxg6 Bxd5 25. Qxd5 c6 26. Qb3 Re4 {
now the Ng6 is cut off, but White still emerges on top after} 27. c3 Ne6 28.
Qc2 Rxe3 (28... Ng5 29. h4 $1) 29. Nh4 $1 {now the rook is cut off!} Nxd4 30.
cxd4 Re6 31. Nf5 {and White is better thanks to the safer king.}) (8... c5 $6
9. O-O Nc6 {is in fact an inferior line as Black is a tempo down compared to
the line 5 d3 Nf6 6 d4 when one of Black's best plans is to play ...c5 and ...
Nc6.} 10. Re1 Re8 {is the engine's suggestion} (10... a6 {was played by
Smyslov, but he was suffocated after} 11. d5 Na7 12. a4 Bd7 13. a5 $16 {
1-0 (42) Karpov,A (2630)-Smyslov,V (2620) Moscow 1972}) (10... d5 $6 11. dxc5
Bxc5 12. a3 {/\b4,Bb2 is a very comfortable IQP position for White.}) (10...
Nb4 11. Bf4 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Be6 13. Rad1 $14 {White is better here due to his
better central control. Now trying to prevent Ng5 by} h6 $2 {loses to} 14. Qe3
$1 {threatening both d5 and dc.}) (10... cxd4 $6 11. Ne2 $16 {is great for
White after Ned4 comes next.}) 11. a3 {preventing ...Nb4} (11. d5 {is also
possible, with a slight edge after} Nb4 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. a3 Na6
15. Qd3 $14) 11... cxd4 (11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Ne2 $14 {/\Nd4}) 12. Ne2
d5 13. Nexd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 $14 {and White is better in this IQP position as
Black's pieces are not particularly active.}) (8... Re8 9. O-O Nbd7 {is an
attempt to follow Petrosian's plan. But even with a knight already on c3 White
has several promising ideas against it.} 10. Re1 Nf8 11. Bg5 (11. Ne2 $5 {
is a good alternative} Ng6 12. Ng3 c6 13. c4 Bf8 14. Rxe8 Qxe8 15. Bg5 Be7 16.
Qb3 {with strong pressure for White.}) (11. d5 $5 {was played by Anand against
Carlsen and even though Carlsen managed to draw White was always better} c6 12.
Bf4 Bd7 13. Bc4 Ng6 14. Bg3 Rc8 15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Bb3 d5 17. Qd3 $14 {½-½ 
(24) Anand,V (2772)-Carlsen,M (2861) Wijk aan Zee 2013}) 11... Be6 (11... Ne6
$5 {is an alternative, though it does block the bishop from c8. It will now
have to be developed to c6 via d7.} 12. Bh4 Bd7 13. Ne2 (13. Bg3 Bc6 14. d5
Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qxd5 {this is around equal, but more
pleasant for White thanks to his better central control.}) 13... Bc6 14. Ng3 g6
15. Bc4 (15. c4 $5 {is interesting, forcing} Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nxd4 17. Qxb7 Ne6
18. Qf3 {with unclear play as in case of ...g5 Black needs to think about the
sacrifice on e6 which will weaken his king.}) 15... Nd5 (15... d5 $6 16. Bd3 {
makes the bishop on c6 rather useless}) 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Bf1 $14 {White has a
slight pull here in view of the better coordination of his pieces and the
safer king.}) 12. Qd2 (12. Ne2 $5 {/\Nf4 is a promising alternative} h6 13. Be3
Ng6 14. Ng3 $14 {/\c4 and/or Nf5 when it is clear White's pieces are much
better placed.}) 12... Ng6 13. d5 (13. Re2 {/\Rae1 is also quite good.}) 13...
Bd7 {0-1 (45) Anand,V (2780)-Kramnik,V (2810) Zuerich 2013} (13... Nxd5 $2 {
drops material in the long line} 14. Bxg6 Nxc3 15. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 16. Bxe8 Ne4
17. Bxe7 Nxd2 18. Bxd8 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Rxd8 20. Bb5 $18) 14. Bxg6 $1 {is a good
improvement over Anand's 14 Bf1, as it wins tempo to double on the e-file.}
hxg6 15. Re3 Nh7 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Rae1 $14 {and Black still hasn't solved all
his problems.}) 9. a3 Re8 10. O-O h6 11. Be3 $5 {This seems to be a new move,
the idea is to follow up with Ne2 and c4 but at the same time avoiding
exchanges along the e-file.} ({The automatic} 11. Re1 {leads to
simplifications after} Bf8 12. Rxe8 Qxe8 13. Ne2 Ne7 14. Ng3 b5 $5 {/\Bb7 and
Black will solve his development problems.}) 11... Bf8 12. Ne2 d5 {Preventing
c4 at the cost of a tempo.} (12... Ne7 {/\Bf5} 13. Ng3 Nfd5 {an attempt to
become active and establish a knight on f4.} 14. Bd2 Ng6 15. c4 Ndf4 16. Bc2 d5
17. c5 $14 {with further advance on the queenside while Black cannot do much
on the kingside.}) (12... g6 $6 {/\Bg7 to improve the position of the bishop.}
13. c4 Bg7 14. Qd2 Kh7 15. Rae1 $16 {/\Ng3 with a tremendous position for
White who is dominating the whole board.}) 13. c3 {/\Qc2} Bd6 (13... Ne4 {
is an attempt to maintain a stronghold on e4, but Black gets under heavy
pressure after} 14. Qc2 Bf5 15. Rae1 Bd6 16. Nf4 Ne7 17. Ne5 {provoking} f6 18.
Nf3 {now the threat is to take on d5 and retreat Bc1 when Black's Ne4 will
hang and also the bishop on f5 will be pinned.} Qd7 {defending the Bf5.} (18...
c6 19. Nh4 {/\f3}) 19. Nh4 (19. Nxd5 $5 Nxd5 20. Bc1 Ng3 {is Black's intended
defence, even though after} 21. fxg3 Bxd3 22. Qxd3 Bxg3 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 $1 (
23... Rxe8 $2 24. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 $140 25. Qg6+ Kh8 26. Qxg3 $18) 24. c4 Nf4 25.
Bxf4 Bxf4 26. Kf2 $1 {/\Re1,d5,Re6 or Qe4 White keeps some pressure.}) 19...
Bh7 20. f3 Bxf4 (20... Ng5 21. Nfg6 {with strong pressure as the simplifying
sequence} Bg3 22. Re2 Bxh4 23. Nxh4 Bxd3 24. Qxd3 {does not make Black's life
easier in view of the fact that White can safely advance on the kingside with
his pawns, taking more space. For example:} Ne6 25. Rfe1 Nf8 26. g4 $14) 21.
Bxf4 Ng5 22. Re2 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 $14 {with ideas to double on the e-file and
advance on the kingside while Black is passive and without counterplay.}) 14.
Qc2 Na5 (14... Ne4 $6 {is now met with} 15. c4 $1) 15. Rae1 Nc4 16. Bc1 {
White successfully regrouped and is ready to expand on the kingside.} b6 {/\c5}
17. Ng3 Rxe1 18. Rxe1 c5 19. Nf5 Bf8 20. Bf4 $14 {White keeps the pressure. 
Conclusion: the line with 5...Nf6 while playable does not solve Black's
opening problems. Black manages to obtain a solid position in all the lines
but the fact that most of the light pieces are still on the board his space
disadvantage is more clearly felt. Coupled with White's starting initiative
and slight development advantage the line is a difficult one to play for Black
and White keeps a pull in all the lines.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2019.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black Castles Long"]
[Black "8.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C42"]
[Annotator "GM Alex Colovic"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[SourceVersionDate "2019.07.09"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 {This move
is the beginning of Black's plan to castle long. He will play ...Be7, ...Be6, .
..Qd7 and ...0-0-0. For a long time this plan was considered as the safest one
and was very popular, even the main proponent of the Petroff Fabiano Caruana
was using it on a regular basis. This, however, changed when Caruana lost a
key game to Karjakin in the Berlin Candidates in 2018 and since then the
fashion changed - in the match with Carlsen Caruana already played the plan
with short castle. But fashion is one thing and solid foundations another, so
this plan is still a very good option for the Black player. In line with our
general approach in the Petroff, we will try to analyse several promising
ideas against it.} 7. Be3 Be7 8. Bc4 $5 {was the move Carlsen used against
Caruana in their last game prior to the match in London. It did manage to take
Caruana by surprise and it still remains an interesting idea.} O-O (8... Be6 {
has been played twice by Duda in his online matches.} 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nd4 $5 {
is an attempt to take immediate advantage of Black's weak pawn on e6.} (10. Qd3
{was Grischuk's choice} Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. c4 Kb8 13. Rhe1 Bf6 {and Black
was rather solid: 0-1 (33) Grischuk,A (2766)-Duda,J (2737) chess.com INT 2018})
(10. Qe2 {since So's game was played later than Grischuk's we can assume this
was some sort of an improvement.} Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. h4 Bf6 13. h5 h6 14.
g4 a6 15. c4 Kb8 {with unclear play with chances for both sides. 1-0 (47) So,W
(2780)-Duda,J (2737) chess.com INT 2018}) 10... Nxd4 (10... Qd7 $5 {is
probably better, as after} 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qf3 e5 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. Qxc6+ bxc6
15. f3 {the endgame while theoretically somewhat better for White should be a
draw.}) 11. Qxd4 e5 (11... Bf6 $6 12. Qe4 Qc8 13. O-O-O O-O 14. f4 $16 {
is a dream position for White who will continue to advance on the kingside.}) (
11... O-O 12. O-O-O b5 {/\a5,b4 if possible} 13. Qg4 Qd7 14. Rhe1 $14 {looks
slightly more pleasant for White in view of his central pressure.}) 12. Qe4 (
12. Qb4 $5 b6 $140 13. Qe4 {is the subtle engine refinement, gaining more
control over the light squares.}) 12... c6 13. O-O-O O-O {1/2-1/2 (58)
Brunello,M (2294)-Yu,J (2268) Batumi GEO 2018} 14. c4 $1 Qc8 {/\Qf5} 15. f3 (
15. c5 {is tempting, but Black has compensation after} d5 16. Qxe5 Bf6 17. Qg3
Qf5 18. Rhe1 Rae8 $1 {/\Re4-b4}) 15... Qf5 16. a4 $14 {with some pressure.}) (
8... Bf5 {this is possible, but not very advisable, as it doesn't solve the
problem of the attack on f7.} 9. Qe2 Qd7 10. O-O-O a6 {is probably best} (10...
Bg6 $6 11. Bb5 {/\Ne5} Bh5 12. h3 {/\g4} a6 13. Bc4 b5 $140 $2 14. Bd5 $16 {
/\g4 as the black king is left without a safe spot to reside.}) (10... Be6 $6 {
wasting time like this makes me wonder why Black didn't play this move in one
go on move 8.} 11. Bb5 a6 $2 12. Ne5 $1 dxe5 13. Rxd7 Bxd7 14. Bc4 $18 {
1-0 (38) So,W (2765)-Erenburg,S (2589) chess.com INT 2019}) 11. h3 O-O 12. g4
Be6 13. Kb1 b5 14. Bxe6 Qxe6 (14... fxe6 15. Bc1 $14 {is a tad bit better for
White due to the vulnerability of the e6-pawn.}) 15. Rhe1 $14 {with some
initiative for White, who is better centralised.}) 9. Qd2 Ne5 (9... Bf5 $6 {
was Caruana's choice, but it's not the best one. Carlsen's play is exemplary:}
10. O-O-O Qd7 11. Kb1 Rfe8 12. h4 Bf8 (12... Bf6 13. Bg5 $1) 13. h5 h6 14. Be2
$1 {White wants to push g4 and in order to do that he needs to play Nd4 first,
to which Black may reply ...Ne5 so the Bc4 is removed in time.} (14. Rdg1 $5 {
is an interesting and more blunt attempt} Bg4 15. Nh2 $1 Ne5 $1 16. Bb3 Bf5 17.
f4 Ng4 18. Nxg4 Bxg4 19. f5 d5 $1 {with unclear play.}) 14... Bg4 15. Nh2 Bxe2
16. Qxe2 Ne5 $6 {/\Qc6,Nc4, but it doesn't work.} (16... Rad8 $1 {is the best
move for Black, but even here} 17. g4 d5 18. Rhg1 Ne5 19. b3 {is a position
where it is Black who should be more careful - White is trying to attack and
Black needs to walk a tight rope with his counterplay.}) 17. Bc1 Qc6 18. f4 Nc4
19. Qd3 Qe4 20. g4 Ne3 21. Rde1 Qxd3 22. cxd3 Nd5 23. Reg1 $16 {and in spite
of the exchange of queens White kept strong attack on the kingside in: 1/2-1/2
(41) Carlsen,M (2842)-Caruana,F (2822) Saint Louis USA 2018}) (9... Be6 10.
Bxe6 fxe6 11. O-O-O $14 {is a typical position that is better for White - he
can advance on the kingside and play against the e6-pawn while Black is devoid
of counterplay.}) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. O-O-O Qxd2+ 12. Rxd2 $14 {is a typical
endgame in these lines when Black plays ...Ne5. At first sight it may seem
that Black is doing quite alright here - better structure and no problems, but
this is not so - the control of the d-file and the possibility of a minority
attack on the kingside (plus the "normal" advance on the queenside) make this
endgame better for White. A classical game in this structure is the game
Caruana-Ponomariov from the King's Tournament in Bucharest in 2013. Although
Black saved the draw he was thoroughly outplayed from what seemed an innocuous
position. Here's a short analysis of how this position can be further played
out.} Bf5 {0-1 (26) Gunina,V (2528)-Kashlinskaya,A (2440) Satka 2018} 13. Re1
$1 Rae8 (13... Rad8 $140 $2 14. Bf4 $1 Rxd2 15. Kxd2 e4 16. f3 $16 {wins a
pawn for White.}) 14. a4 $1 {this move introduces ideas to take on a7 and then
free the bishop by a5.} a6 15. Bb3 {/\Rd5} Be4 (15... c6 16. Rde2 e4 17. Bb6
Bd8 18. a5 $14) 16. f3 Bc6 17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 f6 19. Red1 $14 {with the
better bishop and the ability to further advance on the queenside, while Black
cannot easily do the same on the kingside, White has the more pleasant endgame.
} *

