1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7
8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 {This is the tabiya of this variation and here White
has more moves at his disposal. But even though many moves are possible, the
general ideas are not that many - apart from the pawn advances h4-h5 or h3,g4
and c4, a lot depends on the timing of the Nd4 jump and the consequences of it.
This makes the play very concrete.} (9... a6 {has recently been tried by
Mamedyarov, but it doesn't have an independent value, as after} 10. Be2 (10. b3
h6 11. Be2 {1-0 (41) Anand,V (2776)-Mamedyarov,S (2809) Moscow RUS 2018}) 10...
Qd7 11. h4 {it transposes to the line with 9...Qd7 10 h4 a6.}) (9... Bxa2 $6 {
looks insane, but White should know the refutation:} 10. b3 a5 11. Kb2 a4 12.
Ra1 (12. Kxa2 {is a good alternative} axb3+ 13. Kxb3 Ra5 14. Kb2 Qa8 15. Rb1
$16 {and the king can hide on c1.}) 12... axb3 13. cxb3 Bxb3 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15.
Kxb3 Qa1 16. Qc1 (16. Qb2 Qd1+ 17. Qc2 Qa1 {1/2-1/2 (77) Bologan,V (2665)
-Humeau,C (2203) Calvi 2008}) 16... Na5+ 17. Kc2 Qa4+ 18. Kb1 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Qxc4
{1/2-1/2 (77) Bologan,V (2665)-Humeau,C (2203) Calvi 2008} 20. Kc2 $16 {
and Black shouldn't have enough for the piece.}) 10. a3 $5 {was played in the
crucial game Karjakin-Caruana in Berlin, so it deserves attention.} a6 {
became the preferred choice after the Karjakin-Caruana game.} (10... h6 11. Nd4
Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Rg8 (12... O-O $2 {is what the engine happily wants to play at
low depth, but the attack that is coming after} 13. Rg1 $1 {makes it change
its mind.}) 13. Be2 c5 (13... a6 {was an attempt at an improvement, though the
position remains unpleasant for Black after} 14. c4 O-O-O 15. Qc3 g6 16. b3 Bg4
17. f3 Be6 18. Rhe1 $14 {when White can improve his position with moves like
Kb2, a4-a5, the pawn moves on the kingside will depend on circumstances and
the idea of c5 is also always in the air. The game continuation showed that
Black has difficulties playing under these conditions without any counterplay.}
Rge8 19. Kb1 h5 20. Bf2 Qc6 21. Bd3 d5 22. c5 $1 Bd7 23. Bd4 $16 {with a dream
position for White: 1/2-1/2 (41) Alekseenko,K (2639)-Timofeev,A (2580) St
Petersburg RUS 2018}) (13... Qa4 {was a move mentioned by Karjakin after the
game as a preferable one, though the position remains more pleasant for White:}
14. f4 O-O-O 15. Kb1 Kb8 16. Bf3 $14 {and since Black has an active queen on
the queenside, with the more active bishops White can advance on the kingside
by g4 etc.}) 14. Be3 d5 $6 {a bit too weakening.} (14... O-O-O $142 15. Rhe1
Rge8 16. Bf3 d5 17. Bf4 $14 {White keeps some central pressure with a typical
set-up of "rooks in front and bishops from the sides" in this line of the
Petroff.}) 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Bf3 Bg4 $2 {a bad practical decision by Caruana.} (
{He suggested} 16... f5 {as an improvement, but there is no doubt that White
is very comfortable here after some simple moves like} 17. Bf2 $14 {/\Rhe1,
taking advantage of the weaknesses on the e-file.}) 17. Bxd5 $1 Bxd1 18. Rxd1
Qc7 19. c4 $44 {with excellent compensation for White who went on to win an
excellent game. 1-0 (48) Karjakin,S (2763)-Caruana,F (2784) Berlin 2018}) ({
the point of the move is that Black cannot castle long:} 10... O-O-O $2 11. Nd4
Nxd4 {allowing White to take on e6 leads to a typical better position for
White.} 12. Qxd4 {with a double attack on a7 and g7. This is one of the main
tactical ideas for White, forcing Black to spend a tempo on defence of the a7
or g7 pawns before castling.}) (10... Bf6 {has also been tried lately.} 11. h4
O-O-O 12. Nd4 $5 {looks like an improvement.} (12. Ng5 Bf5 13. Bb5 h6 14. Nf3
a6 15. Ba4 Be4 {and Black is fine, as he managed to push White's pieces
backwards. ½-½ (42) Andreikin,D (2722)-Bu Xiangzhi (2729) Hengshui CHN 2019})
12... Bxd4 (12... Nxd4 $2 13. Bxd4 {hitting a7 and f6 is the point.}) 13. cxd4
d5 14. Bf4 $14 {in this symmetrical position White can play for a very long
time trying to use the power of his unopposed dark-squared bishop.} (14. Qc3 $5
{/\b4 and a4 is an interesting engine suggestion, although of course both
moves 14 Qc3 and 14 Bf4 can be combined with the idea of queenside expansion.})
) 11. Nd4 $5 {an interesting attempt and a small psychological trap.} (11. h4 {
has been played by Vachier and Andreikin, with similar ideas to 10 h4.}) 11...
Nxd4 12. Bxd4 {here lies the trap. A Petroff player who has forgotten his
preparation will play the usual move in such situations, the move also played
by Li Chao} Rg8 $2 {as Black almost never castles short in this line. But this
is one of those rare exceptions when castling short is the way to go! If you
compare the position to the comment to Black's 12...0-0 in the 10...h6 line
you will notice that here the pawn is still on h7, thus making it much more
difficult for White to create an attack.} (12... O-O $1 13. Rg1 Rfc8 14. g4 c5
15. Be3 b5 16. g5) 13. c4 $1 {is stronger, with the idea of Qc3.} (13. Bd3 $6 {
this was a rapid game, so both players probably played more by feeling.} h6 $2
(13... g6 $8 14. Rhe1 O-O-O 15. h3 $14 {/\g4,f4}) 14. Bh7 Rh8 15. Be4 $16 {
1-0 (32) Bacrot,E (2718)-Li Chao2 (2732) Liaocheng CHN 2018}) 13... O-O-O 14.
Qc3 g6 15. Kb1 $14 {with a typical better position for White who can prepare a
kingside advance by f3,g4 and if possible h4-h5.} *

