1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7
8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 10. b3 $5 {has been played by Carlsen.} a6 (10... Bf6
11. h3 (11. Nd4 {is a later attempt} Bxd4 (11... Nxd4 {massive exchanges on d4
don't solve Black's problems completely.} 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O 14. Bd3
Bf5 15. Rhe1 Bxd3 16. Rxd3 Rfe8 17. Rde3 Rxe3 18. Qxe3 $14 {and with the
control of the e-file White has a little bit of something.}) 12. Bxd4 f6 13. c4
O-O-O {1/2-1/2 (27) Lu Shanglei (2628)-Wang Yue (2699) Huocheng County CHN 2017
} (13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 {due to the pawn on a7 Black still cannot castle
queenside, but insisting on it doesn't bring much good either.} b6 15. Be2
O-O-O $6 16. Bf3 $36) 14. Bc3 Rhe8 15. Kb2 {is a typical position that the
engines like, but players of the Petroff are quite happy in them - usually the
bishop pair cannot do much damage against Black's ultra-solid set-up and
normally the White players are avoiding these positions.}) 11... O-O-O 12. g4 {
grabbing kingside space is one of White's possible plans in these structures.}
h6 13. Bg2 Kb8 14. Rhe1 Rhe8 (14... g5 {is the engine's preference with a 0.00
evaluation.} 15. Kb2 Rde8 16. a4 {typical play by White in such positions,
making "small" improvements left and right and waiting for an opportune moment
to jump to d4.} Bg7 {/\f5} 17. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 f5 20. f3
Rhf8 21. Bf1 fxg4 22. fxg4 Rf4 23. Qd3 {/\Bg2 and possible doubling on the
e-file. As usual in this line, White's tiny pressure lasts for a very long
time.}) 15. Kb2 a6 {transposes to Carlsen-Hou Yifan, via the move-order 10 b3
Bf6 11 h3 0-0-0 12 g4 h6 13 Bg2 Kb8 14 Rhe1 Rhe8} 16. Re2 {A characteristic
moment. Both sides have finished development, but while White still has ideas
how to improve his position, the same cannot be said for Black and this makes
White's position much easier to play.} (16. Ng1 $5 {is a curious suggestion of
Lc0, with the idea of Ne2-f4.}) (16. a4 {is another typical move to make.})
16... Qe7 {Black gets the queen to f8, out of the harm's way on the central
files, but this appears to be too slow.} (16... h5 $5 {is the engine's
suggestion} 17. g5 Be5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Qxd7 Rxd7 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Rxd7 Bxd7
22. h4 {and White is on the better side of what should probably be a draw.})
17. Rde1 (17. Nd4 {was possible} Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Qf8 20. f4 $14)
17... Qf8 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Bd7 21. f4 $14 {White has a tiny
edge and we know what usually happens in those positions when Carlsen is
playing. 1-0 (54) Carlsen,M (2844)-Hou,Y (2673) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) (10...
O-O-O {this allows the exchange of the bishop on e6 and this is generally in
White's favour.} 11. Nd4 a6 {preventing Bb5.} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. g3 $14 {
the engine wants to play 13 g4, but this makes more sense - the bishop can
come out to h3 to put pressure on the e6-pawn. This is not always effective
though, as we can see below.} d5 14. Bg2 $5 {makes sense, as the bishop on g2
discourages ...e5 while the pawn on e6 is safely defended, as we could see in
the game.} (14. Bh3 {it's natural to pin everything along the h3-c8 diagonal,
but Black is quickly evacuating it and can safely defend the e6-pawn.} Kb8 15.
Rhe1 Rhe8 16. f4 Bf6 {White is theoretically better - pair of bishops and
pressure along the central files, especially targeting the e6-pawn, but Black
has it all covered and doesn't feel worse. The engine's evaluation of
something like 0.07 probably is as precise as it can be and this translates as
"a playable position for both sides."} 17. Bc5 $5 {in order to prevent ...Qd6}
(17. Kb1 Qd6 $1 {/\e5: ½-½ (34) Vachier Lagrave,M (2804)-Caruana,F (2823)
London 2016}) 17... g6 {/\Qg7} 18. Kb2 Qf7 19. Qf2 Qg7 20. Qf3 {and the game
goes on, as the attempt to simplify by} d4 21. cxd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 23. c3
{drops the pawn on e6.}) 14... Bf6 (14... Qd6 $5 15. f4 Bf6 16. Kb2 Rhe8 17.
Rhe1 Kb8 {is similar to the game, but with the bishop on g2 Black cannot
easily push ...e5.} 18. Qf2 Qf8 19. Rd3 {defending c3 in advance} g6 20. Kb1
Qg7 21. Qd2 {and the complex middlegame struggle goes on, with White putting
the pressure and Black containing it.}) 15. Bc5 ({The engine wants to exchange
bishops by} 15. Bg5 $5 Qf7 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. f4 $14 {and this isn't entirely
without reason as White can put pressure on Black's centre by using the
central files and the pawn breaks c4 and f5.}) 15... g6 16. Rhe1 Rhe8 17. Re3
Kb8 18. Qe1 Qf7 19. c4 $36 {using the fact that the knight on c6 can be taken
in case Black move the d5-pawn. Now after the more or less forced} Be7 20. Bxe7
Qxe7 21. Kb2 {><a3} (21. Kb1 Qa3) 21... Qf6+ 22. Kb1 dxc4 23. Bxc6 Rxd1+ 24.
Qxd1 bxc6 25. Qe2 Rd8 $1 26. Rxe6 Rd1+ 27. Qxd1 Qxe6 28. Qd2 {is a slightly
better queen endgame for White which Black should be able to draw.}) 11. h3
O-O-O (11... h5 {is a direct attempt to stop White's kingside expansion.} 12.
Be2 O-O-O 13. Rhe1 Kb8 (13... Bf6 14. Nd4 {taking advantage of the fact that
Black cannot take twice on d4.} g6 {in this position it is not so good for
White to take on e6 since his light-squared bishop and kingside structure are
not ideal for the typical play against the e6-d5 centre.} (14... Nxd4 $6 15.
Bxd4 Qe7 (15... Bxd4 $6 16. Qxd4 Kb8 17. Qxg7 Rhg8 18. Qf6 Rxg2 19. Bxh5 Bxh3
20. Re7 $16 {leaves White a pawn up.}) 16. Kb2 g6 17. Bf3 $14 {with nagging
pressure along the central files.}) 15. c4 (15. Nxe6 $6 fxe6 $11 {/\Qg7,d5.})
15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 $14 {/\Bf3 when White will have the
"Karpovian" bishop from his game with Uhlmann from Madrid 1973 - his pawns on
the same colour as the bishop on the queenside will limit the opponent's
bishop while his own will work on another diagonal.}) 14. Kb2 (14. Nd4 {
is a more direct attempt} Bf6 15. c4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 g6 18. Qf6 $14
{/\Bf3, with a similar position as the one above with the "Karpovian"
light-squared bishop.}) 14... d5 (14... Bf6 15. Bg5 $5 (15. Nd4 {is always a
valid alternative, leading to similar positions we've already seen.}) 15... Qe7
(15... Bxg5 16. Nxg5 Bf5 17. Bc4 Bg6 18. Nf3 {/\Nh4} h4 19. Qf4 $14 {with more
freedom in the movement of White's pieces. As usual, it's not much, just that
Black needs to be careful about more things.}) 16. h4 Bxg5 (16... Rde8 17. Bd3
$5 {/\Be4, now that the knight is not defended by the queen.} Qd8 18. Be4 Ne5
19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. Qxd8+ Bxd8 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. c4 $14 {the "Karpovian" bishop
favours White again.}) 17. hxg5 f6 18. Bc4 Ne5 19. Bxe6 Qxe6 20. gxf6 Qxf6 21.
Nxe5 dxe5 22. Qe3 $14 {an isolated pawn usually means a +/=, though in
practice a good defender should be able to draw.}) 15. Nd4 Bf6 16. f4 {Vachier
prefers to put the bishop on f3 after the pawn has been more actively placed
on f4.} (16. Nxc6+ Qxc6 17. Bd4 {is the typical maneuver Vachier employed two
moves later.} Bxd4 18. Qxd4 g6 (18... f6 $6 {avoids putting more pawns on
light squares, but this undermines the position of the bishop on e6.} 19. Bf3 {
/\c4} Qd6 20. c4 $16) 19. Bf3 Qd6 20. Qf6 $14 {with some pressure thanks to a
few small advantages: the better bishop, dark-square weaknesses on the
kingside and pressure along the central files.}) 16... g6 17. Bf3 Rhe8 18.
Nxc6+ Qxc6 19. Bd4 Bh4 (19... Bxd4 20. Qxd4 {is a more favourable version for
White than the one arising from the immediate 16 Nc6 since the pawn on f4
further increases the control over the dark squares.}) 20. Re5 $1 (20. Bf2 Bf6
21. Bd4 Bh4 22. Bf2 Bf6 23. g4 hxg4 24. hxg4 d4 $1 {equalises for Black: 1/2-1/
2 (37) Vachier Lagrave,M (2788)-Li,C (2755) Stavanger 2016}) 20... f6 (20...
Bf6 $140 21. c4 $1 Bxe5 22. Bxe5 Bf5 23. cxd5 Qc5 24. g4 hxg4 25. hxg4 Bc8 26.
a3 $44 {with wonderful compensation for White.}) (20... Qd6 21. Bxd5 $1 {
winning a pawn} Bxd5 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Be5 Qe6 24. Qxd5 $16) 21. Re3 Qd7 22. a4
$16 {with strong pressure as Black's position is rather loose.}) (11... Bf6 12.
g4 h6 13. Bg2 O-O-O {- 11...0-0-0 12 g4 h6 13 Bg2 Bf6}) 12. Be2 $1 {this looks
more promising, not allowing Black the counterplay against the g4-pawn.} (12.
g4 h5 $1 {allows Black to stabilise the structure on the kingside and obtain
satisfactory position.} (12... h6 13. Bg2 Bf6 14. Rhe1 (14. Nd4 $5) 14... Rhe8
15. Kb2 Kb8 {transposes to Carlsen-Hou Yifan, via the move-order 10 b3 Bf6 11
h3 0-0-0 12 g4 h6 13 Bg2 Kb8 14 Rhe1 Rhe8}) 13. g5 Ne5 (13... g6 14. Nd4 Nxd4
15. Bxd4 Rhe8 16. Bg2 d5 17. Kb2 Bd6 $11) 14. Bg2 Nxf3 15. Bxf3 g6 (15... f6 {
1/2-1/2 (54) Zhu,J (2363)-Kashlinskaya,A (2445) Shanghai CHN 2017} 16. Qd4 $5
c5 17. Qh4 fxg5 18. Bxg5 Bxg5+ 19. Qxg5 Bxh3 20. Rdg1 {with some pressure for
White.}) 16. h4 d5 $11 {and Black obtains good central control at same time
keeping the dark-squared bishops to keep control over the dark squares.}) 12...
d5 (12... h6 $6 13. Nd4 $1 {is an already familiar motif, with g7 and a7
targets if Black takes on d4.}) (12... Bf6 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qe7 15. Kb2 {
/\Bf3 with pressure in a very similar position to the one we had after 10...a6
11 h3 h5 12 Be2 0-0-0 13 Rhe1 Bf6 14 Nd4 Nd4 15 Bd4 Qe7 16 Kb2}) 13. Nd4 (13.
Rhe1 {is possible, with Nd4 to come sooner rather than later.}) 13... g6 {
Black is removing the g7-pawn (so it doesn't hang in case a white queen
appears on d4) and is preparing for Nxe6 fxe6 when the typical regrouping is ..
.Bf6 and ...Qg7.} 14. Rhe1 Rhe8 (14... Nxd4 $6 15. Bxd4 Rhe8 16. Qh6 $1 {
is somewhat annoying.}) 15. Kb2 (15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. g4 $14 {is another way to
continue.}) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 {/\Qh6} h5 (16... c5 $6 {is too weakening} 17.
Be5 h5 18. Bf3 $14 {and White's bishops (and king!) are definitely better than
their Black counterparts.}) 17. Be5 Qc6 18. Bf3 $14 {with ideas like Qf4,Bf6
and g4 White definitely has the easier play here.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
