1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7
8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 10. h4 $1 {I take this as the main move, as it is
rather direct, introducing the threat of Ng5, but in fact the alternatives are
of equal practical value. We are trying to come up with promising ideas, so
take your pick according to your taste.} h6 ({Curiously enough, Black can for
the time being ignore the threat of Ng5, but that won't last for too long.} 
10... a6 11. Be2 $5 (11. Ng5 Bf5 $1) 11... O-O-O $140 (11... h6 12. Nd4 Nxd4
13. Bxd4 Rg8 14. c4 {when White manages this set-up of Bd4 and Qc3 he is
usually succeeds in putting good pressure.} O-O-O 15. Qc3 g5 16. hxg5 hxg5 17.
Kb1 {and the pawn on g5 will be a constant worry for Black as will be the
threat of an invasion along the h-file.}) 12. Ng5 {/\Ne6 will be better for
White as after fxe6 Black won't be able to comfortably play ...d5, ...g6 in
view of a fast kingside advance by g4 and h5:} Bf6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 (13... Qxe6
14. Qd5 $1 $14 {is just better for White with the pair of bishops.}) 14. g4 $1
g6 15. h5 $16) (10... O-O-O $6 11. Ng5 Bxg5 $140 12. hxg5 $1 $16 {shows the
main idea behind 10 h4.}) 11. b3 {This move prevents ...0-0-0.} (11. Nd4 $5 {
is a more direct continuation and it has been played by Caruana recently.} Nxd4
12. Bxd4 Rg8 13. c4 (13. Kb1 {was played in a blitz game and it followed
already familiar patterns:} O-O-O 14. c4 Qc6 $6 (14... c5 $1 {prevents White's
desired set-up} 15. Bc3 d5 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 Rxd5 18. Rxd5 Bxd5 $11) 15.
Qc3 $1 {this set-up is always favourable for White} g6 16. Be2 h5 17. b3 Bg4
18. Bxg4+ hxg4 {1/2-1/2 (34) Caruana,F (2828)-Harikrishna,P (2726) Saint Louis
USA 2019} 19. Qg3 f5 20. Rde1 $16 {the bishop on e7 is rather hapless.}) 13...
c5 $1 (13... O-O-O $6 14. Qc3 $1) 14. Bc3 O-O-O 15. Qe3 g5 (15... Rde8 16. Kb1
Bf6 17. Qg3 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qc6 {½-½ (31) Nisipeanu,L (2672)-Wang,Y (2752)
Medias 2010} 19. b3 $1 {stabilising the position. White ideally wants to place
his bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal. The tactical justification of the move is
that it prevents ...d5:} Rd8 (19... d5 $140 $2 20. cxd5 Bxd5 21. Bb5 $1 Qxb5
22. Rxd5 b6 23. Rhd1 $18 {when Black's position falls apart.}) 20. f3 {/\Bd3-e4
} Kb8 (20... d5 $6 {again doesn't work in view of} 21. cxd5 Bxd5 22. Bd3 {/\Bh7
} f6 23. Rhe1 $16 {it is curious to note that all White's pawns on light
squares limit Black's bishop but do not hinder their own!} Rge8 {preventing
Re7, but losing to} 24. Bf5+ Kb8 25. Qd2 $18 {/\Qf4 and Black is all tied up.})
21. Bd3 f5 22. Rhe1 Bc8 23. Re7 Rd7 24. Rde1 $16 {with an obvious advantage.})
(15... Qa4 $6 {is a naive attempt at activity} 16. Kb1 d5 17. cxd5 Bxd5 {
0-1 (20) Li,C (2643)-Bu,X (2704) Xinghua Jiangsu 2009} 18. b3 Qc6 19. Bd3 $16 {
Black's position is over-extended and it is difficult for him to find a move:}
Bf6 {this drops a pawn, but the alternatives are not better} (19... Rde8 20.
Bf5+ $1 Be6 21. Bh7 Rh8 22. Be4 $18 {/\Bg7}) (19... Bd6 20. Bb5 $1 Qxb5 21.
Rxd5 $16 {/\Rhd1}) 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Qxc5+ Kb8 22. f3 $16) 16. hxg5 hxg5 17.
Be2 (17. b3 {/\Kb2 immediately, leaving the bishop on f1 was also possible.})
17... Rge8 18. b3 d5 {Black sacrifices a pawn in order to liberate his
position.} (18... Bf5 19. Bd3 Bf6 20. Qf3 Bxd3 21. Qxf6 Bg6 22. Qxg5 $16 {
with a clear pawn up.}) 19. cxd5 Bxd5 20. Bf3 Bd6 21. Qxg5 Bxf3 22. gxf3 $16 {
White is a pawn up, but it is doubled, after long defence So managed to save a
draw. 1/2-1/2 (71) Caruana,F (2819)-So,W (2754) Stavanger NOR 2019}) (11. c4 {
an option with a small practical trap.} O-O $1 {this is rarely good in these
lines, but here it is almost the only way to play for Black! This makes the
whole line with 11 c4 an interesting practical choice - if Black doesn't know
or remember that this is one of those rarest cases to castle kingside then
White will get an easy advantage, as shown in the other lines.} (11... Bf6 {
is the most natural move, but after} 12. Nd4 Nxd4 (12... Ne5 13. b3 $1 {
as the bishop on e6 is not getting away.}) 13. Bxd4 {Black has problems to
solve and there is no easy way out.} Qe7 (13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Rg8 15. Bd3 c5
