b4 $1 Ba2+ 22. Kxa2 Qxa4+ 23. Kb1 $1 a5 24. b5 Bf6 25. Qd5+ Kh8 26. Rh3 $1 {
wins for White as his attack is decisive.}) 20. Rhe1 $1 Bd8 (20... Bf6 $2 21.
Bxf5 $18 {><Ng4,Bd5}) (20... gxh6 21. Rxe7 hxg5 22. fxg5 $18 {is a winning
position for White as Black's king cannot survive for long.}) 21. Be2 gxh6 22.
b4 $1 Ba2+ 23. Kxa2 Qxa4+ 24. Kb2 Bf6 25. Bc4+ Kh8 26. Bb3 Qc6 27. Ne6 Nf2 28.
Ra1 Ne4 29. Rxe4 $1 Qxe4 30. Ra4 $1 {><b4,/\Bd5} Qc6 31. Nxf8 Rxf8 32. Rxa7 $14
{White is a pawn up but his king is also more secure. The position remains
sharp but White's prospects are higher.}) 9... Qa4 (9... Nc6 10. h5 h6 11.
O-O-O Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qd5 Bd6 14. Bd3 Qe6 15. Be4 Qxd5 16. Bxd5 $14 {
is a better endgame for White, who can advance on the queenside and controls
the d-file.}) 10. h5 h6 {Black cannot really allow h6.} 11. Bd3 {White already
threatens Bh6.} Re8 12. Kf1 {White's play is very straight-forward. He aimed
all his pieces towards Black's king and didn't even castle queenside in order
not to allow any counterplay there. Now again the threat is Bh6.} Bf8 {Now
White has two promising continuations, both requiring very precise play by
Black.} 13. Nd4 {Nepomniachtchi was probably still in his preparation.} (13.
Rh4 {is what the engine wants to play and it leads to very complicated lines
where Black must be extremely careful not to be blown off the board.} Qd7 (
13... Qa5 14. b4 $1 {this leaves the black queen completely offside} Qa3 15. g4
$16 {/\g5 with a strong attack as all White's pieces are aimed against Black's
king while Black is lagging behind in development and his queen is stranded on
the queenside.}) 14. g4 Nc6 15. g5 Be7 16. Rh2 hxg5 17. h6 {looks dangerous
enough for Black in spite of the engines' optimistic evaluation of only +0.2
for White.} Ne5 (17... g6 18. Nxg5 Ne5 19. Bd4 $40) (17... Qg4 18. Be2 Qf5 19.
hxg7 Bd7 (19... Kxg7 20. Nd4 $18 {and White is actually winning as the attack
is too strong, a typica line being:} Nxd4 21. Bxd4+ f6 22. Bd3) 20. Nd4 Qg6 21.
Re1 Qxg7 22. Nxc6 Bxc6 23. Bd3 Bf6 24. Rh7 Qxh7 (24... Qf8 25. Qd1 $1 {/\Qh5})
25. Bxh7+ Kxh7 26. f4 $1 $16 {opening even more the position on the kingside
in order to get access to the Black king.}) 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. hxg7 Qg4 $8 20.
Be2 Qd7 $8 21. Qc1 $5 (21. Bxg5 Qxd2 22. Bxd2 Kxg7 23. Bc4 $14 {with a
slightly better endgame for White who can still cause problems on the kingside
after Ke2.}) 21... f6 22. Bd3 e4 $5 (22... Qc6 23. Qd1 e4 (23... g4 $2 24. Bh7+
Kxg7 25. Qd3 f5 26. Bxf5 $16) 24. Qh5 (24. a4 {is a shocking move, threatening
Bb5 and forcing Black to take on d3, but it's not the best.} exd3 25. Qxd3 f5
26. Bd4 Qg6 $1 {and Black survives}) 24... Bf5 25. Be2 Kxg7 26. Bd4 Rh8 27.
Qxg5+ {transposes to 22...e4}) 23. Qd1 (23. Bxe4 Qg4) 23... Qc6 24. Qh5 Bf5 25.
Be2 Kxg7 26. Bd4 Rh8 27. Qxg5+ {transposes to 22...e4} Bg6 (27... Kf7 28. Qxf5
Rxh2 29. Bh5+ Kf8 30. Be3 {now Black has to make a lot of only moves to make
it to an acceptable endgame:} Kg7 31. Rd1 Qc4+ 32. Be2 Rh1+ 33. Kg2 Qxe2 34.
Rxh1 Rg8 35. Rh3 Kf7+ 36. Rg3 Rxg3+ 37. Kxg3 Bd6+ 38. Kg2 Qxc2 39. Bd4 Be7 40.
Qd5+ Kf8 41. Qxb7 {which should be drawable.}) 28. Bh5 Rh6 29. Bxg6 Rxg6 (29...
Rxh2 30. Bxe4+ Kf8 31. Qf5 Qe8 32. Bxb7 $16 {White is materially almost equal
while the attack continues.}) 30. Qf5 {again Black must make three only moves
in a row to stay in the game} Qa6+ $8 {the only move, as the alternative is
too difficult for Black - after a lot of only moves he ends up in an inferior
endgame.} (30... Qc4+ 31. Ke1 e3 32. fxe3 c5 33. Qe4 Qf7 34. Qh1 Qe6 35. Rh7+
Kf8 36. Rh8+ Rg8 37. Qh6+ Ke8 38. Be5 {a very nice move!} Qg4 39. Rxg8+ Qxg8
40. Qh5+ Kf8 41. Bh2 $1 Rd8 42. Rd1 Rxd1+ 43. Kxd1 Qxa2 44. Bf4 Qf7 $8 45. Qf5
{and White still keeps the pressure.}) 31. Ke1 e3 $8 32. fxe3 Qd6 $8 33. Qh3
Rg8 $13 {and this is genuinely unclear.}) 13... Qa5 $1 {is safer for Black, as
he can probably navigate the complications after} (13... Qd7 $6 {this is too
risky} 14. Rh3 {/\Rg3 and the attack will be extremely hard to defend against}
Nc6 $2 (14... Qd8 {is what the engines suggest, but then this hasn't really
been a glorious journey for the queen!} 15. Rg3 Kh8 16. Re1 $36) 15. Rg3 $16
Kh8 (15... Qd8 {/\íQh4 again this was more resilient, though far from being
fun to play after} 16. Kg1) 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bd4 $18 Re6 18. Qf4 Qe8 19. Re3 {
1-0 (19) Nepomniachtchi,I (2775)-Nisipeanu,L (2672) Dortmund GER 2019}) 14. b4
(14. c4 Qxd2 15. Bxd2 {is the engines' suggestion, but obviously Black would
be happy to get an endgame!}) 14... Qe5 $8 (14... Qd5 $2 15. Nb5 $16) 15. Rh4
Nc6 $1 (15... d5 16. g4 $1 Nc6 17. g5 $40) 16. Re1 (16. Kg1 d5 17. Nxc6 bxc6
18. Bd4 Qg5 $11 {forces an endgame which is fine for Black.}) 16... d5 (16...
Nxd4 {also leads to an endgame} 17. cxd4 Qf6 18. Rf4 Qg5 19. Qe2 Qxf4 20. Bxf4
Rxe2 21. Bxe2 {the endgame is slightly better for White, but Black should be
able to hold.}) 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bf4 Qxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 20. Kxe1 a5 $1 {
the only way to look for counterplay} 21. b5 cxb5 22. Bxb5 Ra7 {should be
tenable for Black.}) 9. O-O-O Bf5 {is probably the best attempt for Black in
this line, played by the likes of Ivanchuk, Jobava and Fridman.} (9... Ne5 {
transposes to 8...Nd7 9 0-0-0 Ne5}) (9... Be6 10. h4 Ne5 11. Ng5 Bf5 (11... Qd7
$6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. b3 $14 {Black doesn't have compensation for the ceded
bishop pair.}) 12. f3 h6 13. Be2 $1 {start of an instructive slow attack} hxg5
14. hxg5 Qd7 15. Rh2 Qe6 16. b3 $16 {White can advance with the pawns with g4,
f4 and also double on the h-file and Black is hard pressed to find defence
against these threats.} f6 17. f4 c6 (17... Ng4 18. Bc4 $18) (17... Nf7 18. Bc4
Qd7 19. Rdh1 $18) 18. fxe5 fxe5 19. Bh5 (19. Rdh1 Kf7 20. Bh5+ Bg6 21. g4 $16 {
White has a stable long-term advantage because of his safer king.}) 19... d5
20. Rdh1 Rad8 21. Kb2 $16 {1-0 (56) Trofimov,V (2394)-Jasinski,M (2419) ICCF
2016}) (9... Re8 10. Bd3 (10. h4 $140 Bg4) 10... Bf6 (10... Bg4 $6 11. h3 Bxf3
12. gxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 $14 {/\f4 and White will use the open g-file to his
benefit while the doubled f-pawns control important squares on the e-file.}) (
10... Be6 11. h4 Qd7 12. h5 Bf5 13. h6 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 g6 15. Kb1 $14 {White's
advantage is not big, but it is again the black king that provides it.}) 11.
Rhg1 $5 Be6 (11... Bg4 $6 {just helps White to make the Rg1 useful immediately
after} 12. h3) (11... Ne5 $6 12. Nxe5 dxe5 (12... Bxe5 13. f4 Bf6 14. g4 $16)
13. g4 $16) 12. Ng5 (12. g4 g6) 12... Bxg5 13. Bxg5 Qd7 14. b3 Ne5 15. Be2 $14
{thanks to the bishop pair.}) (9... a5 10. Bd3 a4 11. a3 Ra5 {is a curious
idea, though it's also curious to know what the rook is doing on a5. There is
more than one good way to play here, I present two:} 12. Rhg1 $5 (12. c4 {
is a natural move too} Re8 (12... Bf6 $140 13. Be4 {forces the rook back in
view of the threat Bc6, while} Rh5 14. h3 $16 {risks losing the rook.}) 13. Be4
Rh5 14. h3 Ne5 15. Qe2 Nxf3 16. Qxf3 Re5 17. Bxb7 {wins a pawn and the ensuing
attempt at counterplay} Rf5 18. Qc6 Bd7 19. Qa6 Bg5 {can easily be dealt with
by} 20. Kb1 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Rxe3 22. Rhe1 $16 {Black's vulnerable queenside
pawns give White an advantage.}) 12... Bf5 13. g4 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qa8 {/\Qa6 is
original to some extent, but White obtains an advantage:} 15. c4 Qa6 16. g5 b5
{Black must seek a queen exchange, otherwise the his queen is stranded on the
queenside.} 17. cxb5 Qxb5 18. Qxb5 Rxb5 19. Rg4 {><a4} Rfb8 20. Rc4 Ne5 21.
Nxe5 dxe5 22. Rd7 (22. Rxc7 $2 Bxa3 $1) 22... Bd6 23. Ba7 $1 {indirectly
defending the pawn on b2.} Ra8 24. Rxa4 Kf8 25. g6 $1 {otherwise the rook is
trapped. The endgame is very tactical and concrete.} hxg6 26. Rh4 Kg8 27. Be3
$16 {White's queenside pawns are more valuable as the a-pawn is already a
passed one while Black cannot easily create one.}) 10. Rg1 {a straight-forward
treatment of the position that hasn't been played too many times.} Qd7 11. h3
Rae8 12. Be2 Bd8 {this is the idea of Black's set-up} 13. Kb1 {is a slower
approach, making a useful move because Black finished with his.} ({The more
direct} 13. g4 {is also possible} Be4 14. h4 f5 15. gxf5 Rxf5 {Black must
create some counterplay as otherwise White just advances with the h-pawn and
weakens Black's king.} (15... Bxf5 $6 16. h5 $16 {/\h6}) 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Rxg5
Ne5 18. Rdg1 Rxg5 19. Rxg5 Qh3 20. b3 Qxh4 21. Qd4 $44 {with good compensation
for the pawn. Also note that White is not forced to play on the kingside as he
can happily go Qa7xb7 if allowed.}) 13... Bg6 14. g4 (14. Bf4 {has been played
in: ½-½ (22) Betker,J (2448)-Lins,T (2453) GER email 2015, but it is a bit
slow.}) 14... f5 15. gxf5 Bxf5 (15... Rxf5 16. Rg3 {White simply piles up on
the g-file. It is obvious that the character of play favours White - he plays
against his opponent's king while Black is only defending.} Bh5 17. Rdg1 Bf6
18. Bc4+ Kh8 19. Nd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Bg6 22. b3 $14 {With the
safer king and play on both wings White is better.}) 16. Rg3 Bf6 17. Rdg1 Kh8 (
17... Bxh3 {is risky:} 18. Nh2 $1 {/\Ng4} Bf5 19. Ng4 Bg6 20. Qd5+ $1 Kh8 21.
Qh1 $1 $44 {is a very nice maneuver, with excellent compensation for White.})
18. h4 Ne5 19. Nd4 Be4 20. h5 a6 (20... h6 $2 21. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 22. Qxh6+ Bh7 {
the same would have followed if 22...Qh7} 23. Rg8+ $1 Rxg8 24. Qxf6+ Rg7 25. h6
$18) (20... c5 $6 21. Nb5) 21. f3 Bd5 22. b3 c5 23. Nf5 Bxb3 (23... Qxf5 24.
Qxd5 Qxh5 25. Bf1 $1 $16 {removing the bishop from the e-file and now the
pawns on d6 and b7 hang.}) 24. axb3 Qxf5 25. h6 g6 26. f4 Nf7 27. Bd3 Qd5 28.
c4 Qe6 29. Qg2 $36 {with strong initiative. Conclusion: these lines do not
offer Black full equality and most of them are rather risky as White manages
to develop a dangerous attack.} *

