Is another move that Caruana has played more than once. The move 9...Nf6 is
analysed in the next chapter.} (9... Ne5 10. Nxe5 {is the simplest solution.
It turns out that the positions after Black recaptures are much more pleasant
for White, who can combine his central control with the positional ideas to
undermine Black's kingside by f4 or g4.} (10. h4) 10... dxe5 11. Bd3 Be6 12.
Qe2 Qe8 (12... Bd6 {is an alternative and the following play is typical for
White in these structures:} 13. Kb1 Qd7 14. f3 f5 15. b3 {first White secures
