$1 $14 {and this is the key move in these structures, fighting for the light
squares and the e4-square in particular} b6 18. h4 $5 {is an interesting plan
with the aim to weaken Black's king} (18. Rhf1 {is a slower way to play} Bd7
19. h3 Rae8 20. a4 Qh4 21. Ka2 {emphasising the slow pace!} Bc8 22. Bb2 Bc5 23.
Qg2 h6 24. Ba3 Bxa3 25. Kxa3 Qg5 26. Kb2 a5 27. Rde1 $14 {with continuous
pressure.}) 18... Rae8 19. g5 Bd7 20. h5 e4 (20... Bc6 {is an attempt to keep
the game closed.} 21. h6 g6 22. Rhe1 Qd8 23. Bc4 $16 {/\Ba3,Bd5. White will
patiently play until the game is opened when the weak black king will tell.})
21. fxe4 fxe4 22. Bc4 e3 23. h6 gxh6 {/\Rf2} 24. Rde1 $1 Qxg5 (24... Rf2 25.
Qh5 Qxg5 26. Qxe8+ $1 Bxe8 27. Bxe3 Qxe3 28. Rxe3 $16) 25. Bxe3 Rxe3 26. Qxe3
Qxe3 27. Rxe3 $16) 13. Kb1 f5 14. Bc4 (14. f3 Qf7 15. b3 Bd6 16. Bc1 {is very
similar to the line above with 12...Bd6, the only difference being the black
queen on f7 here and d7 there.}) 14... Bd6 {from here the bishop controls the
a3-f8 diagonal and White cannot play Qb4 as in the Caruana-Ponomariov game.} (
14... Bf6 $6 15. g4 $1 {fighting for the e4-square} Bxc4 16. Qxc4+ Qf7 17. Qb4
f4 18. Bc5 Rfb8 19. f3 $16 {with a stable advantage for White: ½-½ (41)
Caruana,F (2779)-Ponomariov,R (2751) Bucharest 2013}) 15. g4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4+ Qf7
17. Qb5 f4 (17... b6 $6 18. gxf5 Qxf5 19. Rhg1 $14 {gives White the g-file as
a bonus to the better bishop.}) 18. Bc1 c6 19. Qe2 Bc7 20. Qf3 Rad8 21. Rde1
$14 {White's plan is to expand by b3,c4 and Bb2 with a very pleasant position
to play.}) (9... Re8 10. Bd3 Nf8 $6 {Jobava's idea, but with simple moves
White obtains strong attack:} (10... Nf6 {- 9...Nf6 10 Bd3 Re8}) 11. h4 Bg4 12.
h5 Qd7 (12... h6 13. Rdg1 $1 {/\Nh2 is pretty strong.}) 13. Rdg1 Bf5 14. g4
Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Qe6 16. Kb1 d5 17. g5 $40 {1-0 (43) Wei,Y (2707)-Jobava,B (2702)
Doha 2016}) (9... Nc5 $6 {this is dubious as it lands Black in a well-known
position a tempo down. Here it is usually Black to play as it arises from the
7 Bf4 0-0 8 Qd2 Nd7 9 0-0-0 Nc5 10 Be3.} 10. Bc4 {playing by analogy with the
7 Bf4 line} (10. h4 {is an alternative} Bg4 11. Bc4 Bf6 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Qe3
Qe8 14. Qf4 h5 15. Rde1 Qc6 16. Ng5 $16) 10... Be6 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 12. h4 Qd7 13.
Qd5 (13. Qd3 {/\Ng5}) 13... Qc6 14. Qf5 Qc4 15. Kb1 g6 16. Qh3 h5 17. Nd4 (17.
Nd2 {as in the 7 Bf4 line is also fine:} Qg4 18. Qh2 {/\f3}) 17... Ng7 (17...
Nxd4 18. Rxd4 Qe6 19. Qf3 {/\g4} Bf6 20. Rb4 b6 21. g4 $18 {is just winning
for White who has an unstoppable attack.}) 18. Qf3 (18. g4 c5 $8) 18... d5 (
18... c5 19. Qxb7 Rfe8 20. Qb5 $16 {wins a pawn.}) 19. Bh6 Rfe8 20. g4 c5 21.
gxh5 $1 cxd4 22. hxg6 fxg6 23. Rdg1 $18 {with a winning attack}) (9... Nf6) 10.
Kb1 d5 11. h4 Re8 {Again we take Caruana's choice as the main move.} (11... Bc5
{is a rare move but the idea is the same as in the line after 11...Re8 12 Bd3
Bc5.} 12. Nd4 {now this is possible as the move ...Ne5, which works well for
Black in the line 11...Re8 12 Bd3 Bc5 13 Nd4 Ne5 now lacks idea with the
bishop still being on f1.} Re8 (12... Ne5 13. h5 h6 14. Be2 Re8 15. f3 {
with a transposition.}) 13. h5 h6 14. f3 Ne5 (14... Bf8 15. g4) 15. Be2 {
White is a tempo up compared to the analogous line after 11...Re8 12 Bd3 Bc5
13 Nd4 Ne5 with a transposition.} Bf8 16. g4 c5 17. Nb3 b6 18. g5 $1 $16) (
11... Nf6 {was Anand's choice in 2018, but the position is very easy to play
with White - after all the typical moves Bd3,Ng5,f3,g4 he gets a great
attacking position.} 12. Bd3 Re8 13. Ng5 {- 11...Nf6 12 Bd3 Re8 13 Ng5} h6 (
13... Bd6 14. c4 (14. f3 Bg3 $5 {is Black's idea.}) 14... h6 15. cxd5 hxg5 (
15... cxd5 16. f3 Bg3 {now this doesn't work since Black has played ...h6:} 17.
Nh3 Bxh3 18. Rxh3 Nh5 19. Bxh6 $1 $18) 16. hxg5 Nxd5 17. Bd4 {it is very
