diagonal so when White pushes f4 the knight on h5 won't hang.} b4 18. g5 Nh5
19. Nf4 (19. gxh6 $5 {is a good alternative} bxc3 20. Qxc3 Bf6 21. Bd4 Bxd4 22.
Qxd4 Qf6 23. Qxf6 gxf6 24. Nf2 $14 {with a better endgame for White: at the
moment he's a pawn up and he also has the better structure and can attack
Black's pawns on d5 and c4.}) 19... Ng3 $2 {Anand chose a difficult line as he
had to play only moves all the time. No surprise that he falters.} (19... Nxf4
{was better} 20. Bxf4 Qb6 21. cxb4 Bf5 22. Be3 Qxb4 23. Qxb4 Bxb4 24. Bc1 {
with an equal endgame.}) 20. Rg1 hxg5 21. hxg5 Nxf1 22. Rdxf1 Bf5 23. Qh2 Bxg5
24. Bd4 b3 25. Nh5 bxc2+ 26. Ka1 Bg6 27. Nxg7 Be3 28. Rh1 {1-0 (28) Aronian,L 
(2767)-Anand,V (2768) Saint Louis 2018}) 12. Bd3 Bc5 {This is one of the most
solid lines in the whole Petroff and it is not easy to come up with something
exciting. Below I present an overview of what has been tried so far and I
