21. g5 Nd7 (21... Nh5 22. f4 g6 23. Be2 Ng7 24. Bf3 $14 {White is more
harmonious and what's more he has threats on the kingside.}) 22. Nxd7 Bxh2 (
22... Bxd7 {leads to simplifications but White keeps the initiative in the
endgame} 23. Rxe8+ Bxe8 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 25. c4 Bc6 26. h5 d4 27. h6 Bxf3 28. Qe1
Bc6 29. hxg7 Kxg7 30. Qh4 $36) 23. Nf6+ gxf6 24. gxf6 Qf4 25. Qg2+ Qg3 26.
Qxg3+ Bxg3 27. Rg1 c4 28. Rxg3+ Kh8 29. Be2 Bc8 30. Bd1 Re1 (30... Re6 31. Rg5
{><d5}) 31. Kc1 Be6 32. h5 Re5 33. f4 Rf5 34. Bg4 Rxf6 35. f5 Bd7 36. Kd2 Kg7
37. Ke3 {/\Kd4 should be a draw, but it is White who is trying for more.}) (13.
Rde1 $11 {was Aronian's try from the Batumi Olympiad, but Black easily holds
by simply exchanging everything along the e-file.} Bxe3 14. Rxe3 Rxe3 15. Qxe3
Nf6 16. Re1 Qd6 17. Qe8+ Qf8 18. Qxf8+ Kxf8 19. Kc1 Bd7 {with equality. 1/2-1/
2 (28) Aronian,L (2780)-Caruana,F (2827) Batumi GEO 2018}) (13. Bd4 $11 Bxd4
14. cxd4 Nf6 {theoretically speaking White should be somewhat better here
because of the better bishop and slight development advantage, but it is
difficult to make something out of it:} 15. Qf4 (15. Rde1 Ne4 16. Qf4 Qf6 17.
Qxf6 Nxf6 {transposes to 15 Qf4 Ne4 16 Rde1 Qf6 17 Qf6 Nf6}) (15. Ne5 Ne4 $1
16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Qf4 Be6 {with excellent play for Black.}) 15... Ne4 $1 (15...
Bd7 $6 16. Ne5) (15... Be6 16. Rde1) 16. Rde1 Qf6 17. Qxf6 Nxf6 {transposes to
15 Qf4 Ne4 16 Rde1 Qf6 17 Qf6 Nf6} 18. Kc1 {with the tiniest of theoretical
edges. Of course, this should be a draw.} (18. Ne5 g6 19. a4 Ng4 {1/2-1/2 (34)
Karjakin,S (2782)-Giri,A (2782) Leuven BEL 2018}) 18... Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Kf8 20.
Kd2 h6 21. Ne5 Ng4 22. Nxg4 Bxg4 23. c3 Re8 {1/2-1/2 (33) Nakamura,H (2746)
-Caruana,F (2832) London ENG 2018}) (13. Nd4 $6 Ne5 $1 {and the bishop on d3
is in the way} 14. h5 h6 15. f3 Bf8 16. Be2 c5 17. Nb3 b6 {><Nb3 and Black is
preferable here, especially as taking on d5 is not good:} 18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19.
Rxd5 Bb7 20. Rd2 Nxf3 21. Bxf3 Bxf3 22. Bxh6 Bxh5 $1 23. Bxg7 Bxg7 24. Rxh5
Re1+ 25. Nc1 Rae8 $17) 13... f6 (13... Qb6 $6 14. Rde1 $16) 14. Bf4 Bf8 (14...
Ne5 $6 15. Bxe5 fxe5 16. Ng5 h6 17. Bh7+ Kf8 18. Ne4 Qe7 (18... Bb6 19. Ng3 {
is still very unpleasant for Black who will have unsafe king for quite some
time.}) 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. Rhe1 (20. Rde1 {was the engines' suggestion, but in
either case White has a big advantage thanks to Black's weak king.}) 20... Qc4
21. Bg6 Re6 22. h5 Qg4 23. c4 Qxc4 24. f4 $1 e4 25. f5 Rf6 26. g4 $18 {1/2-1/2
(54) Paravyan,D (2629)-Burg,T (2517) Porto Carras GRE 2018}) (14... Bb6 15. h5
Nc5 16. Nd4 {/\f3 with play along the usual lines.}) 15. Be3 $5 (15. Nd4 Ne5
16. Be2 Bd7 {is fine for Black.}) (15. Rhe1 Nc5 16. Nd4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 {0-1 (43)
Vocaturo,D (2612)-Yankelevich,L (2484) Porticcio FRA 2019} Bd7 $11) 15... Nc5 {
Now this is good as Black is trying to use the pawn on f6 in his favour -
White doesn't have the move Ng5 now as in the line 12...Nc5 13 Ng5.} (15... Bc5
$140 $6 16. Bd4 $1 {and now with the f6-square taken Black cannot comfortably
transpose to the endgame as the move ...Nf6 is not possible.} Bb6 (16... Bxd4
17. cxd4 $16 {/\h5 as Black is very passive.}) 17. h5 Ne5 18. Nxe5 fxe5 19.
Bxb6 axb6 20. h6 g6 21. c4 $14 {with a long-term advantage for White in view
of the black king's vulnerability.}) 16. Bxc5 Bxc5 17. h5 b5 (17... Bg4 $6 18.
Qf4 Qd7 19. h6 $1 g6 20. Bxg6 $5 {this is more exciting, showing White's
potential} (20. c4 {is probably stronger:} Bxf3 21. Qxf3 f5 22. c3 Qe6 23. cxd5
Qxd5 24. Qf4 Qe5 25. Qh4 Qe7 26. Qc4+ Kh8 27. Rhe1 $16 {with permanent
initiative because of the weak king on h8.}) 20... hxg6 21. Qxf6 Re6 22. h7+
Qxh7 23. Qg5 Bh5 24. g4 Qf7 25. Nd4 Bxd4 26. cxd4 Rf8 27. gxh5 Qf4 28. Qg1 g5
29. Rh3 $14 {with play against the king.}) 18. Rde1 Be6 (18... Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1
Bg4 20. Qf4 Bd7 21. Nd4 $36) (18... Bd7 19. Rxe8+ Bxe8 20. Qf4 {/\h6,Nd4 is
very promising for White.}) 19. Nd4 Bd7 (19... Bf7 $2 20. Qf4 {/\Qf5}) 20. Qf4
(20. f4 $5 {is another good move} Qc7 21. h6 g6 22. f5 {/\Ne6} Bxd4 23. cxd4 g5
24. b3 $14 {with a structural advantage for White.}) 20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 $36
Qb8 22. Qf3 Qd6 23. a3 {Black finds it difficult to come up with constructive
moves here.} a5 (23... Re8 $2 24. Rxe8+ Bxe8 25. Qf5 g6 26. Qc8 Qd7 27. Qxd7
Bxd7 28. hxg6 hxg6 29. Bxg6 $16 {wins a pawn.}) 24. Bf5 {Fighting for the
e6-square and the e-file.} Re8 (24... Bxd4 25. cxd4 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Bxe8 27. Qg4
$14 {White's advantage is not very big, but it's stable since Black cannot
easily solve the problem of the bad bishop and unsecure king.}) 25. Rxe8+ Bxe8
26. Qg4 Qe7 27. Be6+ Kf8 28. Nf5 Bxh5 {This simplifies the position, but it
doesn't solve Black's problems.} (28... Qc7 29. f4) 29. Qxh5 Qxe6 30. Qxh7 {
Black still suffers because of his king.} Bxf2 (30... Qg8 31. Qh2 $1) (30...
Qf7 31. g4) 31. g4 a4 (31... g5 $2 32. Qh6+ Kf7 33. Qh2 $1 $16) 32. Qxg7+ Ke8
33. Qc7 Kf8 {And while this may look like a fortress at first sight, in a
practical game White can play this forever. Conclusion: the line with 9...c6
and 10...d5 is one of the main and most reliable defences in the Petroff.
Along the main paths White hasn't managed to find anything tangible, so he is
forced to look for the less explored paths. The ideas of 13 Bg5 and 13 Bf4
seem to be the most promising ones and they offer White ways to obtain
promising playable positions.} *

