1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O
8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Nf6 10. Bd3 Re8 {has been tried by Yu Yangyi, but it
doesn't inspire confidence. This line has been practised in correspondence
chess but the ensuing positions are great to play for White. - 9...Nf6 10 Bd3
Re8} (10... d5 {has been tried 3 times by Wei Yi, though all in rapid and
blitz games.} 11. Rhe1 (11. c4 $5 {is an interesting and very safe attempt as
in the endgame after} dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 {White has greater piece
activity, though Black should be fine} Bd6 (13... a6 14. Rhe1 Re8 15. Bf4 {><c7
}) 14. Bd4 $11) 11... Bg4 12. h3 (12. Bg5 {is an alternative as after} Ne4 (
12... Qd6 {preventing Qf4} 13. Nd4 $1 Rfe8 14. f3 Bd7 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 $14
{with a pleasant position for White with the two bishops and still the
possibility to launch an attack on the kingside.}) 13. Bxe4 (13. Bxe7 $5 Qxe7
14. h3 Bh5 15. Qe3 Rfe8 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nd4 $14 {the bishop on g6
is out of play and White is more active.}) 13... dxe4 14. Qxd8 $5 (14. Bxe7 {
was played twice against Wei Yi, but Black seems to be fine here} Qxe7 15. h3 (
15. Qf4 $6 f5 $1 $15 {1/2-1/2 (78) Nepomniachtchi,I (2773)-Wei Yi (2736)
Abidjan CIV 2019}) 15... Bxf3 (15... Bh5) 16. gxf3 Qe6 {0-1 (32)
Praggnanandhaa,R (2536)-Wei Yi (2736) chess.com INT 2019}) 14... Bxd8 15. Rxd8
exf3 {otherwise Black loses a pawn} 16. gxf3 Bxf3 17. Rd7 c5 18. c4 $14 {
White keeps pressure in this endgame though of course Black's drawing chances
are considerable.}) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 Re8 {transposes to 10...d5 11 Rhe1 Bg4
12 h3 Bf3 13 gf d5} 14. Rg1 $5 (14. f4 {this was Vachier's choice, but it
appears that the advance of the f-pawn to f5 doesn't bring too many benefits}
c5 15. Kb1 Qc7 {is preferred by the engines} (15... Qa5 16. f5 Rad8 17. Rg1 Kh8
18. c4 Qa4 (18... Qxd2 $2 19. Bxd2 d4 20. c3 dxc3 21. Bxc3 $16 {with a better
endgame for White as the bishop pair rules. Vachier went on to win showing
good technique. 1-0 (43) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Wei Yi (2736) Abidjan CIV
2019}) 19. b3 Qc6 20. cxd5 Rxd5 21. Qe2 {continues to be complex, but White
can play on with ideas like Bc1-b2 trying to create threats on the kingside or
to look for a favourable endgame.}) 16. Rg1 Kh8 17. Be2 $5 {/\Bf3} Rad8 18. Bf3
b5 19. Qd3 Qb6 20. Qf1 {/\Qg2 with complicated play for both sides.}) (14. c4
dxc4 15. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 16. Bxd2 Bc5 17. Be3 Bxe3+ 18. fxe3 {is equal, though
White can try to play for the better lighter piece and his central pawn
preponderance.}) 14... Qd6 (14... Bf8 {is possible} 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. h4 (16. c4
$5 dxc4 17. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 {White can try to squeeze water out of stone
here, after all a bishop pair is a bishop pair} Be7 $8 19. c3 Rad8 20. Bh6 g6
21. b4) 16... Nd7 17. h5 Ne5 18. Be2 Nc4 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. Qd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5 {
with a tiny edge thanks to the control of the d-file.}) 15. Kb1 $5 (15. h4 Rad8
16. Kb1 Bf8 17. Bg5 Kh8 {is a complex middlegame with equal chances.}) 15...
Rad8 16. Qc1 {is a very curious maneuver, removing the queen from the d-file,
thus giving the Rd1 more scope on it.} Bf8 17. Bg5 Kh8 18. c4 Qc6 19. Qf4 $13 {
with unclear play.}) (10... Bg4) 11. Rhe1 (11. h4 $5 {this is direct, but
Black can deal with it} d5 (11... Bf8 {was recently tried by the Petroff
connoisseur Fridman, but he ran into difficulties:} 12. Ng5 (12. Bd4 $5 c5 $140
$6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qd3 Qf5 18. Rhe1 $16
{with strong pressure.}) 12... h6 13. f3 c5 14. g4 Qa5 (14... d5 15. Nxf7 $5
Kxf7 16. g5 $40 d4 $1 17. cxd4 Nd5 18. Bf4 c4 $8 19. Bxc4 Bf5 20. Rde1 {
with three pawns for the piece this is evaluated a bit above 0.00 by the
engines, which clearly shows that White has great play here!}) 15. Kb1 b5 16.
Ne4 (16. Nxf7 $1 {again this is very strong, but Sevian's move is good enough.}
) 16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Be6 (17... Rb8 18. Bd5 $14) 18. c4 $1 Qxd2 19. Bxd2 Rac8
20. cxb5 $16 {with a clear pawn up which should be a technically winning
position. 1/2-1/2 (54) Sevian,S (2677)-Fridman,D (2644) Saint Louis USA 2019})
12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Qf4 Be7 $1 {/\Bd6 chasing away the queen from her
dominant position is better} (14... Be6 $6 15. g4 $1 Qd6 16. Qxd6 cxd6 17. Rdg1
$16 {with a clearly superior endgame as the bishops don't compensate for the
awful doubled d-pawns in ½-½ (56) Wei Yi (2741)-Yu Yangyi (2738) Danzhou CHN
2019}) 15. Nd4 Bd6 16. Qf3 Be5 $1 {/\Qf6 is the only way to exchange queens
and stop White's attack. Now} 17. g4 $6 {doesn't work in view of} Qf6 18. Nf5
Bxf5 19. Qxf5 Qxf5 20. Bxf5 g6 21. Bd3 Re6 $15 {is even slightly better for
Black, who will double on the e-file and can attack White's f-pawn by ...Rf6
if necessary.}) 11... Bd7 {this is a very dangerous line for Black.} (11... Bg4
12. h3 (12. Bg5 c6 13. Re2 {is an alternative way to play.}) 12... Bxf3 13.
gxf3 d5 {transposes to 10...d5 11 Rhe1 Bg4 12 h3 Bf3 13 gf d5}) 12. Bd4 h6 (
12... c5 $6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Be4 $16 {><d5,d6}) 13. c4 c5 14. Bc3 ({now} 14.
Bxf6 $6 {is not good in view of the weakening of the long diagonal:} Bxf6 15.
Be4 Qb6 16. c3 Rad8 {/\Qa6,b5} 17. Qxd6 $2 Bc6 $19) 14... a6 (14... Bc6 $6 {
this is slow} 15. Qf4 {/\g4} Nh5 16. Qg4 Nf6 17. Qh3 Bf8 (17... Bd7 18. Bf5 $16
) 18. Qf5 Qc8 $2 (18... Qd7 19. Bxf6 Qxf5 20. Bxf5 gxf6 21. Nh4 $16 {is awful
for Black, but at least he is not immediately lost.}) 19. Rxe8 $1 Qxf5 20.
Rxf8+ {1-0 (20) Hracek,Z (2556)-Cyborowski,L (2526) Czech Republic CZE 2019})
15. g4 $1 Nxg4 16. h3 Bc6 (16... Nf6 $2 17. Rg1 $18) 17. Be4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Ne5
(18... Nf6 $2 19. Rg1 $18 Nxe4 20. Rxg7+ Kf8 21. Qxh6) 19. Rg1 Kh8 20. Qd5 Bf6
21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. Nxe5 dxe5 23. Qxf7 Re7 {1/2-1/2 (43) Ljubicic,L (2596)-Hall,
R (2598) ICCF 2017} 24. Qf3 $14 {White has a very pleasant edge here, as he
has the safer king and can play on the weakened light squares. For example:}
Qf8 25. Qe3 b6 26. Rg6 *

