fxe6 20. f3 Bg5 21. Be3 Bxe3 22. Qxe3 Nc5 23. Rd4 $16) 19. Nxf7 $1 {wins on
the spot} Bxg4 20. Nxd6 Bxd6 21. Qg5 Qc7 22. Qxg4 $18) 11... Be6 12. Qf4 d5 (
12... h6 {is a critical test, but quite a risky one!} 13. Bxh6 (13. Bxf6 {
is a calmer alternative} Bxf6 14. Qe4 (14. Bf5 $5 d5 (14... Bxa2 {looks risky
but it's possible} 15. Rxd6 Qb8 {/\Be7} 16. Qg3 Bc4 17. Re1 {is another
unclear position where White's central domination compensates for the bishop
pair.}) 15. Rhe1 Qb6 (15... g5 {is the engine's choice, but unless this is a
player's preparation nobody will even consider the move! Even so, things are
unclear after} 16. Qg4 h5 17. Qh3 g4 18. Qxh5 Bxf5 19. Qxf5 gxf3 20. Rg1 Bg7
21. gxf3 Re8 22. Rxd5 Qh4 23. Qg5 Qh7 24. Rd7 Re2 25. Rd8+ Re8 26. Rd7 {
White doesn't have more than a repetition here, but if Black wants to continue
things are messy} Rac8 27. Qf4 Rf8 28. Rxb7 Rce8 29. Rd7 Re2 30. Rd2 Rxd2 31.
Qxd2 $13) 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qg3 {/\Ne5 with a complex middlegame.}) 14... g6
15. Bc4 Re8 16. Bxe6 (16. Rhe1 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Rxe1 18. Rxe1 Qd7 19. Qd5 {
should be equal, though White has ideas like Kb1 and Nd2-e4 or c4.}) 16... Rxe6
17. Qxb7 Rb8 18. Qd5 Qb6 $1 {this forces a repetition} 19. Qb3 Qc7 20. Qd5 Qb6
$11) 13... gxh6 14. Qxh6 {/\Ng5} Re8 $8 {this and all the next 20 (!) moves
are the only moves for Black} 15. Ng5 Bf8 16. Bh7+ Kh8 17. Qh4 Ng4 18. Bf5+ Bh6
(18... Nh6 $4 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Nf7+ $18) 19. f4 Qf6 20. Bxe6 Qxf4+ 21. Kb1
fxe6 22. Nh3 Qf5 (22... Qe4 $2 23. Nf2 Nxf2 24. Qxh6+ Kg8 25. Rhf1 Rf8 26. Rxd6
Ng4 27. Qg5+ Kh8 28. Qh4+ Kg8 29. Re1 $16) 23. Rdf1 (23. Rhf1 $5 Qg6 24. Rf3
Rg8 25. Rg3 Qf5 26. a4 {/\Rd6} Rae8 27. Rxd6 Qf1+ 28. Ka2 Qc4+ 29. Ka3 {
is a very unclear position.}) 23... Qg6 24. Rf4 Ne3 25. Rf6 Qxc2+ 26. Ka1 Nf5
27. Qh5 (27. Rxh6+ $6 Nxh6 28. Qxh6+ Qh7 $17) 27... Re7 28. Ng5 Qxg2 (28... Kg8
$2 29. Rg6+ Rg7 30. Rxg7+ Bxg7 31. Qh7+ Kf8 32. Nxe6+ Kf7 33. Nxg7 Nxg7 34.
Qxc2 $18) 29. Rxh6+ Nxh6 30. Qxh6+ Kg8 31. Qg6+ Rg7 32. Qxe6+ Kf8 33. Qf6+ Kg8
34. Qe6+ $11 {with a perpetual check.}) 13. c4 $5 {An interesting idea by
Svidler.} (13. Rhe1 {was unceremoniously drawn in Karjakin-So at the Riga
Grand Prix 2019. - 11 Bg5 Be6 12 Qf4 d5 13 Rhe1} Re8 14. c4 $5 {again the same
move c4 and the analysis below shows that this is rather dangerous for Black.}
(14. Bb5 Rf8 15. Bd3 {was unceremoniously drawn in Karjakin-So at the Riga
Grand Prix 2019.}) 14... Qa5 (14... d4 15. Qh4 h6 16. Rxe6 fxe6 17. Bxf6 (17.
Bd2 {keeps more pieces on the board and also gives good compensation} Bf8 18.
Ne5 Nd7 19. Qe4 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 Qf6 21. Qe4 Bd6 22. Qxb7 $14) 17... Bxf6 18. Qe4
Rb8 19. h4 {with pretty good compensation where White isn't risking anything
thanks to his absolute light-square control.}) 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qe4 g6 $1 (
16... Bxg5+ {looks too dangerous} 17. Nxg5 Nf6 18. Qh4 Qxa2 19. Nxh7 Qa1+ 20.
Kd2 Qa5+ 21. c3 Rad8 (21... c4 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23. Bxc4 $16) 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23.
Kc2 c4 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. Be4 $14 {and this is better for White because in the
middlegame he has the safer king while in an endgame he will have the better
structure with a passed pawn on the h-file.}) 17. Qh4 $5 {the other moves
promise very little. What follows now is rather wild and while objectively
Black is not losing from a practical aspect it is much easier to be White in
these lines.} (17. a3 Bxg5+ 18. Nxg5 h6) (17. Bc4 Bxg5+ 18. Nxg5 Nf6 19. Qh4
Bxc4 20. Qxc4 Qc7 21. g3 b6 $11) (17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. a3 Rae8 19. Qh4 Kg7 20. Ng5
(20. Ne5 Nf6 21. f4 Qa4 22. Rf1 b5 23. g4 b4 {and Black arrives first.}) 20...
Nf6 21. Re3 {1/2-1/2 (21) Kochan,I (2238)-Deskin,G (2189) ICCF 2018}) 17...
Qxa2 (17... Bf8 $6 18. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 19. c4 Nb4 20. Bf6 {/\Ng5 and a very
strong attack} Nxd3+ 21. Rxd3 Qc7 22. Ng5 {/\Be5} Re7 23. Kc2 (23. Rh3 Rf7 24.
Nxf7 Qxf7 25. Rf3 $14 Bg7 26. Bxg7 Qxg7 27. Qe4 $14 {White is better here
because of the better structure and safer king.}) 23... Rae8 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25.
Qg3 Bg7 26. Ne4 Bd4 27. Qd6 Qxd6 28. Nxd6 Rf8 29. f3 b6 30. b4 $14 {and White
can press in this endgame.}) 18. Rxe6 $5 (18. Bxe7 {allows a perpetual check
after} Rxe7 19. Ng5 Qa1+ 20. Kd2 Qxb2 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. Nxe6+ fxe6 23. Qxg6
Qc3+ 24. Kc1 Qb2+ $11) 18... fxe6 19. Bxe7 {is a calmer alternative, without
too many risks for White} (19. c4 $5 {this is extremely risky for both sides}
Qa1+ (19... Bxg5+ 20. Qxg5 (20. Nxg5 Qa1+ 21. Bb1 Nf6 22. Qf4 Rf8 23. Nxe6 Rf7
24. Ng5 Rff8 25. Ne6 {with a repetition.}) 20... Qa1+ (20... Ne7 21. Ne5 Qa1+
22. Bb1 Rad8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Qf6 Rd1+ $8 25. Kxd1 Qxb1+ 26. Ke2 Qf5 27. Qxe7
Qxe5+ 28. Kf1 Qxb2 29. Qxe6+ {with a most likely draw by a perpetual.}) 21. Bb1
{transposes to 19...Bg5 20 Qg5 Qa1 21 Bb1} Nc3 (21... Nb4 22. Ne5 {/\Ng6 is
dangerous for Black} Na2+ $2 23. Kc2 Nb4+ 24. Kb3 $18) 22. bxc3 Qxc3+ 23. Bc2
Qa1+ 24. Kd2 {an attempt to avoid the repetition, but unfortunately not for
long} Qb2 25. Rc1 a5 26. Ke1 a4 27. Bxg6 hxg6 28. Ne5 Re7 29. Qxg6+ Kh8 30.
Qf6+ Kg8 31. Qg6+ $11) 20. Bb1 Nc3 $1 (20... Qa4 21. Bxe7 Nxe7 22. Ng5 h5 23.
Nxe6 Nc6 24. Nxc5 (24. Qe4 Ne5 $1) 24... Qb4 (24... Qa5 $2 25. Qf6 $18) 25. Ne4
Qxc4+ 26. Bc2 Ne5 27. Nf6+ Kf7 28. Qxc4+ Nxc4 29. Nxe8 Rxe8 30. h4 $14 {
with a theoretical advantage for White in view of the better light piece.}) (
20... Bxg5+ 21. Nxg5 (21. Qxg5 {transposes to 19...Bg5 20 Qg5 Qa1 21 Bb1})
21... Nf6 22. Qf4 Rf8 23. Nxe6 Rf7 24. Nd8 Rf8 25. Ne6 $11 {is a repetition,
the same as in the line 19...Bg5 20 Ng5 Qa1 21 Bb1 Nf6 with a repetition.}) 21.
bxc3 Qxc3+ 22. Bc2 Qa1+ 23. Kd2 Rad8+ 24. Ke2 Rxd1 (24... Qb2 $2 25. Bxe7 Qxc2+
26. Rd2 Rxd2+ 27. Nxd2 $18 {wins for White because Black's king is fatally
weak on the dark squares.}) 25. Bxe7 Rh1 (25... Rd7 26. Bf6 Qa2 27. Qe4 $13 {
is a very messy position, I'd take the three pieces, but obviously it's
chaotic.}) 26. Bd3 (26. Bg5 Qf1+ 27. Ke3 $11 {is an amusing perpetual.} a5 {
and the engine claims Black is winning, with some very complex lines to prove
so.} (27... Qc1+ 28. Kd3 Qf1+ 29. Ke3 $11 {is an amusing perpetual.})) 26...
Qb2+ $11 27. Ke3 b6 (27... Qc1+ 28. Ke2 Qb2+ $11) 28. Bf6 e5 29. Qe4 Qd4+ $1
30. Kd2 Qxe4 31. Bxe4 Kf7 32. Bxe5 Kf8 $1 {/\Re5, which would simplify Black's
task} 33. Bd6+ Kg7 34. Bd5 {and the engines claim Black is better (or winning)
but I'd say things are not that clear for a human over the board.}) 19... Nxe7
(19... Rxe7 20. c4 Rae8 21. cxd5 exd5 22. Qg5 {threatening Bb5. This is very
unclear, but also very likely to end up in some sort of repetition in view of
the vulnerability of the two kings.} Re6 23. Bb1 Qc4+ 24. Bc2 {/\Qd5} Re2 25.
Nd2 Qd4 26. Nf3 Qc4 27. Nd2 $11) 20. Ng5 h5 21. Nxe6 Nc6 22. Qc4 $1 Qa1+ 23.
Kd2 Qxb2 24. Nc7+ Kg7 25. Nxa8 Rxa8 26. Qxc5 {with a very sharp position which
should be around equal.}) 13... Re8 {With this move Black sacrifices pawn for
activity.} (13... Qb6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Rhe1 Rfe8 16. Bc4 Bd6 (16... Bxc4 $6
17. Qxc4 {/\Ne5,><f7} Bf8 18. Ne5 Qe6 19. a4 $1 $14 {shows White's superiority
in the centre.}) 17. Qh4 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Re8 20. Rg1 $14 {with the
bishop pair and some attacking chances White is better.}) 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15.
cxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qf5+ Kg8 18. Qxd5 (18. Rxd5 $5 {is the engine's
preference} Qb6 19. c3 Re2 (19... Qa6 20. Kb1 Re2 21. Rd2) 20. Rd2 Rae8 21.
Rhd1 $14 {is similar to the game in sense that Black has certain compensation
and it is based on his piece activity, while White aims to exchange pieces and
diminish it.}) 18... Qb6 19. c3 Re2 20. Rd2 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 (21. Nxd2 $5 {
invites a king walk after} Rd8 22. Qe4 Rxd2 $5 23. Kxd2 Qxb2+ {but White is
fine:} 24. Ke3 Qxc3+ 25. Kf4 Qd2+ 26. Kg3 Qxa2 27. Qxb7 Qe6 28. f4 {should be
around equal, but White doesn't risk losing here and can possibly try to play
for more.}) 21... Qe6 22. Kb1 Qg4 23. Rg1 {was approximately equal in: ½-½ 
(68) Svidler,P (2737)-Duda,J (2729) Riga LAT 2019. Conclusion: the main line
of the the Petroff where Black castles short is the current battleground and
the pinnacle of the Petroff theory. Carlsen didn't even try to enter this
territory, trusting Caruana's preparation. Theory goes forward though and some
promising ideas have appeared for White, primarily Svidler's treatment
involving the c4-idea, both with and without Rhe1. Both lead to interesting
play where White is the one trying for more.} *

